# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: minimum-total-potential-energy-principle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] In physics, a **conservative force** is a force with the property that the total work done by the force in moving a particle between two points is independent of the path taken.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Equivalently, if a particle travels in a closed loop, the total work done (the sum of the force acting along the path multiplied by the displacement) by a conservative force is zero.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] A conservative force depends only on the position of the object.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] If the force is not conservative, then defining a scalar potential is not possible, because taking different paths would lead to conflicting potential differences between the start and end points.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Gravitational force is an example of a conservative force, while frictional force is an example of a non-conservative force.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Other examples of conservative forces are: force in elastic spring, force due to liquid pressure acting on a surface, electrostatic force between two electric charges, and magnetic force between two magnetic poles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] The last two forces are called central forces as they act along the line joining the centres of two charged/magnetized bodies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] A central force is conservative if and only if it is spherically symmetric.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] where $F_{c}$ is the conservative force, U is the potential energy, and s is the position.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Informally, a conservative force can be thought of as a force that *conserves* mechanical energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Suppose a particle starts at point A, and there is a force *F* acting on it.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Then the particle is moved around by other forces, and eventually ends up at A again.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Though the particle may still be moving, at that instant when it passes point A again, it has traveled a closed path.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] If the net work done by *F* at this point is 0, then *F* passes the closed path test.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Any force that passes the closed path test for all possible closed paths is classified as a conservative force.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] For non-conservative forces, the mechanical energy that is lost (not conserved) has to go somewhere else, by conservation of energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Usually the energy is turned into heat, for example the heat generated by friction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] In addition to heat, friction also often produces some sound energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] The water drag on a moving boat converts the boat's mechanical energy into not only heat and sound energy, but also wave energy at the edges of its wake.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] These and other energy losses are irreversible because of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] A direct consequence of the closed path test is that the work done by a conservative force on a particle moving between any two points does not depend on the path taken by the particle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] This is illustrated in the figure to the right: The work done by the gravitational force on an object depends only on its change in height because the gravitational force is conservative.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] The work done by a conservative force is equal to the negative of change in potential energy during that process.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] For a proof, imagine two paths 1 and 2, both going from point A to point B.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] The variation of energy for the particle, taking path 1 from A to B and then path 2 backwards from B to A, is 0; thus, the work is the same in path 1 and 2, i.e., the work is independent of the path followed, as long as it goes from A to B.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] For example, if a child slides down a frictionless slide, the work done by the gravitational force on the child from the start of the slide to the end is independent of the shape of the slide; it only depends on the vertical displacement of the child.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] is zero the left hand side is zero – therefore statement 2 is true.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Finally, assume that the third statement is true.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] A well-known vector calculus identity states that the curl of the gradient of any function is 0.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] .) Therefore, if the third statement is true, then the first statement must be true as well.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] This shows that statement 1 implies 2, 2 implies 3, and 3 implies 1.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] The term *conservative force* comes from the fact that when a conservative force exists, it conserves mechanical energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] The most familiar conservative forces are gravity, the electric force (in a time-independent magnetic field, see Faraday's law), and spring force.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Many forces (particularly those that depend on velocity) are not force *fields*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] In these cases, the above three conditions are not mathematically equivalent.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] For example, the magnetic force satisfies condition 2 (since the work done by a magnetic field on a charged particle is always zero), but does not satisfy condition 3, and condition 1 is not even defined (the force is not a vector field, so one cannot evaluate its curl).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Accordingly, some authors classify the magnetic force as conservative, while others do not.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] The magnetic force is an unusual case; most velocity-dependent forces, such as friction, do not satisfy any of the three conditions, and therefore are unambiguously nonconservative.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Despite conservation of total energy, non-conservative forces can arise in classical physics due to neglected degrees of freedom or from time-dependent potentials.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Many non-conservative forces may be perceived as macroscopic effects of small-scale conservative forces.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] For instance, friction may be treated without violating conservation of energy by considering the motion of individual molecules; however, that means every molecule's motion must be considered rather than handling it through statistical methods.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] For macroscopic systems the non-conservative approximation is far easier to deal with than millions of degrees of freedom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Examples of non-conservative forces are friction and non-elastic material stress.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] Friction has the effect of transferring some of the energy from the large-scale motion of the bodies to small-scale movements in their interior, and therefore appear non-conservative on a large scale.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] General relativity is non-conservative, as seen in the anomalous precession of Mercury's orbit.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/conservative-force] However, general relativity does conserve a stress–energy–momentum pseudotensor.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In the social sciences, **distance** can refer to a qualitative measurement of separation, such as social distance or psychological distance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The distance between physical locations can be defined in different ways in different contexts.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The distance between two points in physical space is the length of a straight line between them, which is the shortest possible path.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] This is the usual meaning of distance in classical physics, including Newtonian mechanics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] Straight-line distance is formalized mathematically as the Euclidean distance in two- and three-dimensional space.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In Euclidean geometry, the distance between two points A and B is often denoted $|AB|$ .
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In coordinate geometry, Euclidean distance is computed using the Pythagorean theorem.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] There are many ways of measuring straight-line distances.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] For example, it can be done directly using a ruler, or indirectly with a radar (for long distances) or interferometry (for very short distances).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The cosmic distance ladder is a set of ways of measuring extremely long distances.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The straight-line distance between two points on the surface of the Earth is not very useful for most purposes, since we cannot tunnel straight through the Earth's mantle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] Instead, one typically measures the shortest path along the surface of the Earth, as the crow flies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] This is approximated mathematically by the great-circle distance on a sphere.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] More generally, the shortest path between two points along a curved surface is known as a geodesic.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The arc length of geodesics gives a way of measuring distance from the perspective of an ant or other flightless creature living on that surface.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In the theory of relativity, because of phenomena such as length contraction and the relativity of simultaneity, distances between objects depend on a choice of inertial frame of reference.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] On galactic and larger scales, the measurement of distance is also affected by the expansion of the universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In practice, a number of distance measures are used in cosmology to quantify such distances.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] Many abstract notions of distance used in mathematics, science and engineering represent a degree of difference or separation between similar objects.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In statistics and information geometry, statistical distances measure the degree of difference between two probability distributions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] There are many kinds of statistical distances, typically formalized as divergences; these allow a set of probability distributions to be understood as a geometrical object called a statistical manifold.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The most elementary is the squared Euclidean distance, which is minimized by the least squares method; this is the most basic Bregman divergence.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The most important in information theory is the relative entropy (Kullback–Leibler divergence), which allows one to analogously study maximum likelihood estimation geometrically; this is an example of both an *f*-divergence and a Bregman divergence (and in fact the only example which is both).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] Statistical manifolds corresponding to Bregman divergences are flat manifolds in the corresponding geometry, allowing an analog of the Pythagorean theorem (which holds for squared Euclidean distance) to be used for linear inverse problems in inference by optimization theory.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] Other important statistical distances include the Mahalanobis distance and the energy distance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In computer science, an edit distance or string metric between two strings measures how different they are.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] For example, the words "dog" and "dot", which differ by just one letter, are closer than "dog" and "cat", which have no letters in common.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] This idea is used in spell checkers and in coding theory, and is mathematically formalized in a number of different ways, including Levenshtein distance, Hamming distance, Lee distance, and Jaro–Winkler distance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In a graph, the distance between two vertices is measured by the length of the shortest edge path between them.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] For example, if the graph represents a social network, then the idea of six degrees of separation can be interpreted mathematically as saying that the distance between any two vertices is at most six.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] Similarly, the Erdős number and the Bacon number—the number of collaborative relationships away a person is from prolific mathematician Paul Erdős and actor Kevin Bacon, respectively—are distances in the graphs whose edges represent mathematical or artistic collaborations.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In psychology, human geography, and the social sciences, distance is often theorized not as an objective numerical measurement, but as a qualitative description of a subjective experience.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] For example, psychological distance is "the different ways in which an object might be removed from" the self along dimensions such as "time, space, social distance, and hypotheticality".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In sociology, social distance describes the separation between individuals or social groups in society along dimensions such as social class, race/ethnicity, gender or sexuality.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] Most of the notions of distance between two points or objects described above are examples of the mathematical idea of a metric.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The distance between distinct objects is always positive.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] Distance is symmetric: the distance from x to y is always the same as the distance from y to x.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] As an exception, many of the divergences used in statistics are not metrics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] This does not define a metric on the set of such subsets: the distance between overlapping sets is zero, and this distance does not satisfy the triangle inequality for any metric space with two or more points (consider the triple of sets consisting of two distinct singletons and their union).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The word **distance** is also used for related concepts that are not encompassed by the description "a numerical measurement of how far apart points or objects are".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The **distance travelled** by an object is the length of a specific path travelled between two points, such as the distance walked while navigating a maze or the distance marked by a milepost or an odometer.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] This can even be a **closed distance** along a closed curve which starts and ends at the same point, such as a ball thrown straight up, or the Earth when it completes one orbit.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] This is formalized mathematically as the arc length of the curve.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The distance travelled may also be signed: a "forward" distance is positive and a "backward" distance is negative.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The displacement in classical physics measures the change in position of an object during an interval of time.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] While distance is a scalar quantity, or a magnitude, displacement is a vector quantity with both magnitude and direction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] In general, the vector measuring the difference between two locations (the relative position) is sometimes called the **directed distance**.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The function has positive values at points *x* inside Ω, it decreases in value as *x* approaches the boundary of Ω where the signed distance function is zero, and it takes negative values outside of Ω.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] However, the alternative convention is also sometimes taken instead (i.e., negative inside Ω and positive outside).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/distance] The concept also sometimes goes by the name oriented distance function/field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In physics, **electromagnetic radiation** (**EMR**) or an **electromagnetic wave** (**EMW**) is a self-propagating wave of the electromagnetic field that carries momentum and radiant energy through space.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It encompasses a broad spectrum, classified by frequency (inversely proportional to wavelength), ranging from radio waves, microwaves, infrared, visible light, ultraviolet, X-rays, to gamma rays.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] All forms of EMR travel at the speed of light in a vacuum and exhibit wave–particle duality, behaving both as waves and as discrete particles called photons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation is produced by accelerating charged particles such as from the Sun and other celestial bodies or artificially generated for various applications.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Its interaction with matter depends on wavelength, influencing its uses in communication, medicine, industry, and scientific research.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Radio waves enable broadcasting and wireless communication, infrared is used in thermal imaging, visible light is essential for vision, and higher-energy radiation, such as X-rays and gamma rays, is applied in medical imaging, cancer treatment, and industrial inspection.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Higher energy EMR, especially in the UV and above, has been associated with negative health effects.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In quantum mechanics, an alternate way of viewing EMR is that it consists of photons, uncharged elementary particles with zero rest mass which are the quanta of the electromagnetic field, responsible for all electromagnetic interactions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Quantum electrodynamics is the theory of how EMR interacts with matter on an atomic level.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Quantum effects provide additional sources of EMR, such as the transition of electrons to lower energy levels in an atom and black-body radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell's equations and their solutions (Panofsky–Phillips equations) indicate that a component of the electric field and magnetic field has an amplitude that decreases inversely with the distance between the source and the observer (1/r), allowing it to be detectable at large distances.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These components are transverse to the direction of propagation (**n**) of the radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] One has $\mathbf {E} \perp \mathbf {B} \perp \mathbf {n}$ , with **E** and **B** related by: $\mathbf {B} ={\frac {\mathbf {n} \times \mathbf {E} }{c}}$ Note also that these fields propagate through space at the speed of light, i.e. at 299,792,458 m/s.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation is produced by accelerating charged particles and can be naturally emitted, as from the Sun and other celestial bodies, or artificially generated for various applications.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The energy in electromagnetic waves is sometimes called radiant energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The electromagnetic waves' energy does not need a propagating medium to travel through space; they move through a vacuum at the speed of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electric and magnetic fields obey the properties of superposition.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Thus, a field due to any particular particle or time-varying electric or magnetic field contributes to the fields present in the same space due to other causes.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Further, as they are vector fields, all magnetic and electric field vectors add together according to vector addition.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For example, in optics two or more coherent light waves may interact and by constructive or destructive interference yield a resultant irradiance deviating from the sum of the component irradiances of the individual light waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The electromagnetic fields of light are not affected by traveling through static electric or magnetic fields in a linear medium such as a vacuum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, in nonlinear media, such as some crystals, interactions can occur between light and static electric and magnetic fields—these interactions include the Faraday effect and the Kerr effect.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In refraction, a wave crossing from one medium to another of different density alters its speed and direction upon entering the new medium.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The ratio of the refractive indices of the media determines the degree of refraction, and is summarized by Snell's law.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Light of composite wavelengths (natural sunlight) disperses into a visible spectrum passing through a prism, because of the wavelength-dependent refractive index of the prism material (dispersion); that is, each component wave within the composite light is bent a different amount.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] EM radiation exhibits both wave properties and particle properties at the same time (known as wave–particle duality).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Both wave and particle characteristics have been confirmed in many experiments.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Wave characteristics are more apparent when EM radiation is measured over relatively large timescales and over large distances while particle characteristics are more evident when measuring small timescales and distances.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For example, when electromagnetic radiation is absorbed by matter, particle-like properties will be more obvious when the average number of photons in the cube of the relevant wavelength is much smaller than 1.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It is not so difficult to experimentally observe non-uniform deposition of energy when light is absorbed, however this alone is not evidence of "particulate" behavior.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Rather, it reflects the quantum nature of *matter*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A quantum theory of the interaction between electromagnetic radiation and matter such as electrons is described by the theory of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic waves can be polarized, reflected, refracted, or diffracted, and can interfere with each other.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Some experiments display both the wave and particle natures of electromagnetic waves, such as the self-interference of a single photon.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In homogeneous, isotropic media, electromagnetic radiation is a transverse wave, meaning that its oscillations are perpendicular to the direction of energy transfer and travel.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The electric and magnetic parts of the field in an electromagnetic wave stand in a fixed ratio of strengths to satisfy the two Maxwell's equations that specify how one is produced from the other.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In dissipation-less (lossless) media, these E and B fields are also in phase, with both reaching maxima and minima at the same points in space.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In the far-field EM radiation which is described by the two source-free Maxwell curl operator equations, a time-change in one type of field is proportional to the curl of the other.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These derivatives require that the E and B fields in EMR are in phase.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An important aspect of light's nature is its frequency.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The frequency of a wave is its rate of oscillation and is measured in hertz, the SI unit of frequency, where one hertz is equal to one oscillation per second.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Light usually has multiple frequencies that sum to form the resultant wave.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Different frequencies undergo different angles of refraction, a phenomenon known as dispersion.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A monochromatic wave (a wave of a single frequency) consists of successive troughs and crests, and the distance between two adjacent crests or troughs is called the wavelength.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Waves of the electromagnetic spectrum vary in size, from very long radio waves longer than a continent to very short gamma rays smaller than atom nuclei.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] where *v* is the speed of the wave (*c* in a vacuum or less in other media), *f* is the frequency, and *λ* is the wavelength.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As waves cross boundaries between different media, their speeds change but their frequencies remain constant.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic waves in free space must be solutions of Maxwell's electromagnetic wave equation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Two main classes of solutions are known, namely plane waves and spherical waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The plane waves may be viewed as the limiting case of spherical waves at a very large (ideally infinite) distance from the source.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Both types of waves can have a waveform which is an arbitrary time function (so long as it is sufficiently differentiable to conform to the wave equation).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As with any time function, this can be decomposed by means of Fourier analysis into its frequency spectrum, or individual sinusoidal components, each of which contains a single frequency, amplitude, and phase.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Such a component wave is said to be *monochromatic*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Interference is the superposition of two or more waves resulting in a new wave pattern.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] If the fields have components in the same direction, they constructively interfere, while opposite directions cause destructive interference.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Additionally, multiple polarization signals can be combined (i.e. interfered) to form new states of polarization, which is known as parallel polarization state generation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] James Clerk Maxwell derived a wave form of the electric and magnetic equations, thus uncovering the wave-like nature of electric and magnetic fields and their symmetry.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Because the speed of EM waves predicted by the wave equation coincided with the measured speed of light, Maxwell concluded that light itself is an EM wave.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell's equations were confirmed by Heinrich Hertz through experiments with radio waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Out of the four equations, two of the equations that Maxwell refined were Faraday's Law of Induction and Ampère's circuital law, which he extended by adding the displacement current term to the equations himself.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell thought that the displacement current, which he viewed as the motion of bound charges, gave rise to the magnetic field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The other two equations are Gauss's law and Gauss's law for magnetism.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell's equations established that some charges and currents (*sources*) produce local electromagnetic fields near them that do not radiate.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Currents directly produce magnetic fields of a magnetic-dipole–type that die out with distance from the current.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In a similar manner, moving charges pushed apart in a conductor by a changing electrical potential (such as in an antenna) produce an electric-dipole–type electrical field, but this also declines with distance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Neither of these behaviours is responsible for EM radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Instead, they only efficiently transfer energy to a receiver very close to the source, such as inside a transformer.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The near field has strong effects on its source, with any energy withdrawn by a receiver causing increased *load* (decreased electrical reactance) on the source.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The near field does not propagate freely into space, carrying energy away without a distance limit, but rather oscillates, returning its energy to the transmitter if it is not absorbed by a receiver.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This far part of the electromagnetic field *is* electromagnetic radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The far fields propagate (radiate) without allowing the transmitter to affect them.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This causes them to be independent in the sense that their existence and their energy, after they have left the transmitter, is completely independent of both transmitter and receiver.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Due to conservation of energy, the amount of power passing through any closed surface drawn around the source is the same.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The power density of EM radiation from an isotropic source decreases with the inverse square of the distance from the source; this is called the inverse-square law.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Field intensity due to dipole parts of the near field varies according to an inverse-cube law, and thus fades with distance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The distinction between near field and radiated field is illustrated by the Panofsky–Phillips equations, which give the general expression of the electric and magnetic fields produced by an arbitrary distribution of charges and currents.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The terms of the Panofsky–Phillips equations can be separated into two categories: The "near field" terms have a **$1/r^{2}$** dependence, and are significant only in the immediate vicinity of the sources.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The "far field" terms have a **$1/r$** dependence.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Due to their slower decrease with distance, they dominate as one moves away from the sources.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] By contrast, the term associated with the changing static electric field of the particle and the magnetic term that results from the particle's uniform velocity are both associated with the near field, and do not comprise electromagnetic radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An anomaly arose in the late 19th century involving a contradiction between the wave theory of light and measurements of the electromagnetic spectra that were being emitted by thermal radiators known as black bodies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Physicists struggled with this problem unsuccessfully for many years, and it later became known as the ultraviolet catastrophe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1900, Max Planck developed a new theory of black-body radiation that explained the observed spectrum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Planck's theory was based on the idea that black bodies emit light (and other electromagnetic radiation) only as discrete bundles or packets of energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1905, Albert Einstein proposed that light quanta be regarded as real particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Later the particle of light was given the name photon, to correspond with other particles being described around this time, such as the electron and proton.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] where *h* is the Planck constant, $\lambda$ is the wavelength and *c* is the speed of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This is sometimes known as the Planck–Einstein equation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In quantum theory (see first quantization) the energy of the photons is thus directly proportional to the frequency of the EMR wave.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Experimental measurements demonstrated that the energy of individual ejected electrons was proportional to the *frequency*, rather than the *intensity*, of the light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Furthermore, below a certain minimum frequency, which depended on the particular metal, no current would flow regardless of the intensity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These observations appeared to contradict the wave theory, and for years physicists tried to find an explanation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1905, Einstein explained this phenomenon by resurrecting the particle theory of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Because of the preponderance of evidence in favor of the wave theory, however, Einstein's ideas were met initially with great skepticism among established physicists.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Eventually Einstein's explanation was accepted as new particle-like behavior of light was observed, such as the Compton effect.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As a photon is absorbed by an atom, it excites the atom, elevating an electron to a higher energy level (one that is on average farther from the nucleus).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] When an electron in an excited molecule or atom descends to a lower energy level, it emits a photon of light at a frequency corresponding to the energy difference.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Since the energy levels of electrons in atoms are discrete, each element and each molecule emits and absorbs its own characteristic frequencies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Immediate photon emission is called fluorescence, a type of photoluminescence.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An example is visible light emitted from fluorescent paints, in response to ultraviolet (blacklight).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Many other fluorescent emissions are known in spectral bands other than visible light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Delayed emission is called phosphorescence.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Quantum mechanics also governs emission, which is seen when an emitting gas glows due to excitation of the atoms from any mechanism, including heat.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As electrons descend to lower energy levels, a spectrum is emitted that represents the jumps between the energy levels of the electrons, but lines are seen because again emission happens only at particular energies after excitation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An example is the emission spectrum of nebulae.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Rapidly moving electrons are most sharply accelerated when they encounter a region of force, so they are responsible for producing much of the highest frequency electromagnetic radiation observed in nature.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These phenomena can be used to detect the composition of gases lit from behind (absorption spectra) and for glowing gases (emission spectra).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Spectroscopy (for example) determines what chemical elements comprise a particular star.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Shifts in the frequency of the spectral lines for an element, called a redshift, can be used to determine the star's cosmological distance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The modern theory that explains the nature of light includes the notion of wave–particle duality.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The theory is based on the concept that every quantum entity can show wave-like or particle-like behaviors, depending on observation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The observation led to the collapse of the entity's wave function.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] If it is based on the Copenhagen interpretation, the observation does really collapse the wave function; for the many-worlds interpretation, all possible outcomes of the collapse happened in parallel universes; for the pilot wave theory, the particle behaviour is simply determined by waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The duality nature of a real photon has been observed in the double-slit experiment.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Together, wave and particle effects fully explain the emission and absorption spectra of EM radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The matter-composition of the medium through which the light travels determines the nature of the absorption and emission spectrum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These bands correspond to the allowed energy levels in the atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Dark bands in the absorption spectrum are due to the atoms in an intervening medium between source and observer.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The atoms absorb certain frequencies of the light between emitter and detector/eye, then emit them in all directions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A dark band appears to the detector, due to the radiation scattered out of the light beam.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For instance, dark bands in the light emitted by a distant star are due to the atoms in the star's atmosphere.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In empty space (vacuum), electromagnetic radiation travels at the speed of light, c , 299,792,458 meters per second (approximately 186,000 miles per second).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The reason for this is that in matter the electric and magnetic fields of the wave are slowed because they polarize the charged particles in the medium they pass through.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The oscillating electric field causes nearby positive and negative charges in atoms to move slightly apart and together, inducing an oscillating polarization, creating an electric polarization field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The oscillating magnetic field moves nearby magnetic dipoles, inducing an oscillating magnetization, creating an induced oscillating magnetic field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These induced fields, superposed on the original wave fields, slow the wave (Ewald–Oseen extinction theorem).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The amount of slowing depends on the electromagnetic properties of the medium, the electric permittivity and magnetic permeability.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In the SI system of units, empty space has a vacuum permittivity of $\epsilon _{\text{0}}=$ 8.854×10−12 F/m (farads per meter) and a vacuum permeability of $\mu _{\text{0}}=$ 1.257×10−6 H/m (henries per meter).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In a medium that is isotropic and linear, which means the electric polarization is proportional to the electric field $\mathbf {D} =\epsilon \mathbf {E}$ and the magnetization is proportional to the magnetic field $\mathbf {H} ={1 \over \mu }\mathbf {B}$ .
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] If the permittivity and permeability of the medium is constant for different frequency EM waves, this is called a *non-dispersive* medium.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In this case all EM wave frequencies would travel at the same velocity, and the waveshape stays constant as it travels.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However in real matter $\epsilon$ and $\mu$ typically vary with frequency, this is called a *dispersive* medium.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In dispersive media different spectral bands have different propagation characteristics, and an arbitrary wave changes shape as it travels through the medium.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation of wavelengths other than those of visible light were discovered in the early 19th century.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The discovery of infrared radiation is ascribed to astronomer William Herschel, who published his results in 1800 before the Royal Society of London.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Herschel used a glass prism to refract light from the Sun and detected invisible rays that caused heating beyond the red part of the spectrum, through an increase in the temperature recorded with a thermometer.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These "calorific rays" were later termed infrared.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1801 German physicist Johann Wilhelm Ritter discovered ultraviolet in an experiment similar to Herschel's, using sunlight and a glass prism.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ritter noted that invisible rays near the violet edge of a solar spectrum dispersed by a triangular prism darkened silver chloride preparations more quickly than did the nearby violet light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ritter's experiments were an early precursor to what would become photography.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ritter noted that the ultraviolet rays (which at first were called "chemical rays") were capable of causing chemical reactions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1862–64 James Clerk Maxwell developed equations for the electromagnetic field which suggested that waves in the field would travel with a speed that was very close to the known speed of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell therefore suggested that visible light (as well as invisible infrared and ultraviolet rays by inference) all consisted of propagating disturbances (or radiation) in the electromagnetic field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Radio waves were first produced deliberately by Heinrich Hertz in 1887, using electrical circuits calculated to produce oscillations at a much lower frequency than that of visible light, following recipes for producing oscillating charges and currents suggested by Maxwell's equations.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Hertz also developed ways to detect these waves, and produced and characterized what were later termed radio waves and microwaves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Wilhelm Röntgen discovered and named X-rays.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] After experimenting with high voltages applied to an evacuated tube on 8 November 1895, he noticed a fluorescence on a nearby plate of coated glass.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In one month, he discovered X-rays' main properties.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The last portion of the EM spectrum to be discovered was associated with radioactivity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Henri Becquerel found that uranium salts caused fogging of an unexposed photographic plate through a covering paper in a manner similar to X-rays, and Marie Curie discovered that only certain elements gave off these rays of energy, soon discovering the intense radiation of radium.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The radiation from pitchblende was differentiated into alpha rays (alpha particles) and beta rays (beta particles) by Ernest Rutherford through simple experimentation in 1899, but these proved to be charged particulate types of radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, in 1900 the French scientist Paul Villard discovered a third neutrally charged and especially penetrating type of radiation from radium, and after he described it, Rutherford realized it must be yet a third type of radiation, which in 1903 Rutherford named gamma rays.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] EM radiation (the designation 'radiation' excludes static electric and magnetic and near fields) is classified by wavelength into radio, microwave, infrared, visible, ultraviolet, X-rays, and gamma rays.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Arbitrary electromagnetic waves can be expressed by Fourier analysis in terms of sinusoidal waves (monochromatic radiation), which in turn can each be classified into these regions of the EMR spectrum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For certain classes of EM waves, the waveform is most usefully treated as *random*, and then spectral analysis must be done by slightly different mathematical techniques appropriate to random or stochastic processes.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In such cases, the individual frequency components are represented in terms of their *power* content, and the phase information is not preserved.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Such a representation is called the power spectral density of the random process.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Random electromagnetic radiation requiring this kind of analysis is, for example, encountered in the interior of stars, and in certain other very wideband forms of radiation such as the zero-point wave field of the electromagnetic vacuum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The behavior of EM radiation and its interaction with matter depends on its frequency, and changes qualitatively as the frequency changes.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Lower frequencies have longer wavelengths, and higher frequencies have shorter wavelengths, and are associated with photons of higher energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] There is no fundamental limit known to these wavelengths or energies, at either end of the spectrum, although photons with energies near the Planck energy or exceeding it (far too high to have ever been observed) will require new physical theories to describe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation phenomena with wavelengths ranging from one meter to one millimeter are called microwaves; with frequencies between 300 MHz (0.3 GHz) and 300 GHz.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] When radio waves impinge upon a conductor, they couple to the conductor, travel along it, and induce an electric current on the conductor surface by moving the electrons of the conducting material in correlated bunches of charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] At radio and microwave frequencies, EMR interacts with matter largely as a bulk collection of charges which are spread out over large numbers of affected atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In electrical conductors, such induced bulk movement of charges (electric currents) results in absorption of the EMR, or else separations of charges that cause generation of new EMR (effective reflection of the EMR).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An example is absorption or emission of radio waves by antennas, or absorption of microwaves by water or other molecules with an electric dipole moment, as for example inside a microwave oven.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These interactions produce either electric currents or heat, or both.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Like radio and microwave, infrared (IR) is reflected by metals (and also most EMR, well into the ultraviolet range).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, unlike lower-frequency radio and microwave radiation, infrared EMR commonly interacts with dipoles present in single molecules, which change as atoms vibrate at the ends of a single chemical bond.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It is consequently absorbed by a wide range of substances, causing them to increase in temperature as the vibrations dissipate as heat.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The same process, run in reverse, causes bulk substances to radiate in the infrared spontaneously (see thermal radiation section below).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Infrared radiation is divided into spectral subregions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] While different subdivision schemes exist, the spectrum is commonly divided as near-infrared (0.75–1.4 μm), short-wavelength infrared (1.4–3 μm), mid-wavelength infrared (3–8 μm), long-wavelength infrared (8–15 μm) and far infrared (15–1000 μm).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Some animals, such as snakes, have thermo-sensitive membranes (pit organs) that can detect temperature differences, allowing them to sense infrared radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Natural sources produce EM radiation across the spectrum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] EM radiation with a wavelength between approximately 400 nm and 700 nm is directly detected by the human eye and perceived as visible light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Other wavelengths, especially nearby infrared (longer than 700 nm) and ultraviolet (shorter than 400 nm) are also sometimes referred to as light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As frequency increases into the visible range, photons have enough energy to change the bond structure of some individual molecules.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It is not a coincidence that this happens in the visible range, as the mechanism of vision involves the change in bonding of a single molecule, retinal, which absorbs a single photon.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The change in retinal causes a change in the shape of the rhodopsin protein it is contained in, which starts the biochemical process that causes the retina of the human eye to sense the light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Visible light is able to affect only a tiny percentage of all molecules.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Usually not in a permanent or damaging way, rather the photon excites an electron which then emits another photon when returning to its original position.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This is the source of color produced by most dyes.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] When a photon is absorbed, the retinal permanently changes structure from cis to trans, and requires a protein to convert it back, i.e. reset it to be able to function as a light detector again.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Photosynthesis becomes possible in this range as well, for the same reason.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A single molecule of chlorophyll is excited by a single photon.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In plant tissues that conduct photosynthesis, carotenoids act to quench electronically excited chlorophyll produced by visible light in a process called non-photochemical quenching, to prevent reactions that would otherwise interfere with photosynthesis at high light levels.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Limited evidence indicate that some reactive oxygen species are created by visible light in skin, and that these may have some role in photoaging, in the same manner as ultraviolet A.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Infrared, microwaves, and radio waves are known to damage molecules and biological tissue only by bulk heating, not excitation from single photons of the radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As frequency increases into the ultraviolet, photons now carry enough energy (about three electron volts or more) to excite certain doubly bonded molecules into permanent chemical rearrangement.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] DNA is also indirectly damaged by reactive oxygen species produced by ultraviolet A (UVA), which has energy too low to damage DNA directly.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This is why ultraviolet at all wavelengths can damage DNA, and is capable of causing cancer, and (for UVB) skin burns (sunburn) that are far worse than would be produced by simple heating (temperature increase) effects.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] At the higher end of the ultraviolet range, the energy of photons becomes large enough to impart enough energy to electrons to cause them to be liberated from the atom, in a process called photoionisation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The energy required for this is always larger than about 10 electron volt (eV) corresponding with wavelengths smaller than 124 nm (some sources suggest a more realistic cutoff of 33 eV, which is the energy required to ionize water).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This high end of the ultraviolet spectrum with energies in the approximate ionization range, is sometimes called "extreme UV".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ionizing UV is strongly filtered by the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation composed of photons that carry minimum-ionization energy, or more (which includes the entire spectrum with shorter wavelengths), is therefore termed ionizing radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] (Many other kinds of ionizing radiation are made of non-EM particles.) Electromagnetic-type ionizing radiation extends from the extreme ultraviolet to all higher frequencies and shorter wavelengths, which means that all X-rays and gamma rays qualify.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These are capable of the most severe types of molecular damage, which can happen in biology to any type of biomolecule, including mutation and cancer, and often at great depths below the skin, since the higher end of the X-ray spectrum, and all of the gamma ray spectrum, penetrate matter.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Most UV and X-rays are blocked by absorption first from molecular nitrogen, and then (for wavelengths in the upper UV) from the electronic excitation of dioxygen and finally ozone at the mid-range of UV.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Only 30% of the Sun's ultraviolet light reaches the ground, and almost all of this is well transmitted.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Visible light is well transmitted in air, a property known as an atmospheric window, as it is not energetic enough to excite nitrogen, oxygen, or ozone, but too energetic to excite molecular vibrational frequencies of water vapor and carbon dioxide.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Absorption bands in the infrared are due to modes of vibrational excitation in water vapor.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, at energies too low to excite water vapor, the atmosphere becomes transparent again, allowing free transmission of most microwave and radio waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Finally, at radio wavelengths longer than 10 m or so (about 30 MHz), the air in the lower atmosphere remains transparent to radio, but plasma in certain layers of the ionosphere begins to interact with radio waves (see skywave).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This property allows some longer wavelengths (100 m or 3 MHz) to be reflected and results in shortwave radio beyond line-of-sight.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, certain ionospheric effects begin to block incoming radiowaves from space, when their frequency is less than about 10 MHz (wavelength longer than about 30 m).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The basic structure of matter involves charged particles bound together.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] When electromagnetic radiation impinges on matter, it causes the charged particles to oscillate and gain energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The ultimate fate of this energy depends on the context.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It could be immediately re-radiated and appear as scattered, reflected, or transmitted radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It may get dissipated into other microscopic motions within the matter, coming to thermal equilibrium and manifesting itself as thermal energy, or even kinetic energy, in the material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This happens for infrared, microwave, and radio wave radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Intense radio waves can thermally burn living tissue and can cook food.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In addition to infrared lasers, sufficiently intense visible and ultraviolet lasers can easily set paper afire.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ionizing radiation creates high-speed electrons in a material and breaks chemical bonds, but after these electrons collide many times with other atoms eventually most of the energy becomes thermal energy all in a tiny fraction of a second.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This caveat also applies to UV, even though almost all of it is not ionizing, because UV can damage molecules due to electronic excitation, which is far greater per unit energy than heating effects.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Infrared radiation in the spectral distribution of a black body is usually considered a form of heat, since it has an equivalent temperature and is associated with an entropy change per unit of thermal energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, "heat" is a technical term in physics and thermodynamics and is often confused with thermal energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Any type of electromagnetic energy can be transformed into thermal energy in interaction with matter.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Thus, *any* electromagnetic radiation can "heat" (in the sense of increase the thermal energy temperature of) a material, when it is absorbed.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The inverse or time-reversed process of absorption is thermal radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Much of the thermal energy in matter consists of random motion of charged particles, and this energy can be radiated away from the matter.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The resulting radiation may subsequently be absorbed by another piece of matter, with the deposited energy heating the material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The electromagnetic radiation in an opaque cavity at thermal equilibrium is effectively a form of thermal energy, having maximum radiation entropy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Bioelectromagnetics is the study of the interactions and effects of EM radiation on living organisms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The effects of electromagnetic radiation upon living cells, including those in humans, depends upon the radiation's power and frequency.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For low-frequency radiation (radio waves to near ultraviolet) the best-understood effects are those due to radiation power alone, acting through heating when radiation is absorbed.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For these thermal effects, frequency is important as it affects the intensity of the radiation and penetration into the organism (for example, microwaves penetrate better than infrared).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It is widely accepted that low frequency fields that are too weak to cause significant heating could not possibly have any biological effect.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Some research suggests that weaker *non-thermal* electromagnetic fields (including weak ELF magnetic fields, although the latter does not strictly qualify as EM radiation) and modulated RF and microwave fields can have biological effects, though the significance of this is unclear.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] All UV frequencies have been classed as Group 1 carcinogens by the World Health Organization.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ultraviolet radiation from sun exposure is the primary cause of skin cancer, the most common type of cancer among fair-skinned people.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] UV radiation damages DNA and cells as well as causing mutations that block DNA repair.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Visible and infrared light may increase photoaging, but sunscreens do not generally protect against these effects.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The World Health Organization has classified radio frequency electromagnetic radiation as Group 2B—possibly carcinogenic.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This group contains possible carcinogens such as lead, coffee, and automobile exhaust.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The heat ray is an application of EMR that makes use of microwave frequencies to create an unpleasant heating effect in the upper layer of the skin.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A publicly known heat ray weapon called the Active Denial System was developed by the US military as an experimental weapon to deny the enemy access to an area.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A death ray is a theoretical weapon that delivers heat ray based on electromagnetic energy at levels that are capable of injuring human tissue.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An inventor of a death ray, Harry Grindell Matthews, claimed to have lost sight in his left eye while working on his death ray weapon based on a microwave magnetron from the 1920s (a normal microwave oven creates a tissue damaging cooking effect inside the oven at around 2 kV/m).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] Electromagnetic waves are predicted by the classical laws of electricity and magnetism, known as Maxwell's equations.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] There are nontrivial solutions of the homogeneous Maxwell's equations (without charges or currents), describing *waves* of changing electric and magnetic fields.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] Thus Maxwell's equations connect the vacuum permittivity $\varepsilon _{0}$ , the vacuum permeability $\mu _{0}$ , and the speed of light, *c*0, via the above equation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] This relationship had been discovered by Wilhelm Eduard Weber and Rudolf Kohlrausch prior to the development of Maxwell's electrodynamics, however Maxwell was the first to produce a field theory consistent with waves traveling at the speed of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] These are only two equations versus the original four, so more information pertains to these waves hidden within Maxwell's equations.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] The electric and magnetic field waves in the far-field travel at the speed of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] They have a special restricted orientation and proportional magnitudes, $E_{0}=c_{0}B_{0}$ , which can be seen immediately from the Poynting vector.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] The electric field, magnetic field, and direction of wave propagation are all orthogonal, and the wave propagates in the same direction as $\mathbf {E} \times \mathbf {B}$ .
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] Also **E** and **B** far-fields in free space, which as wave solutions depend primarily on these two Maxwell's equations to remain in phase with each other.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] From the viewpoint of an electromagnetic wave traveling forward, the electric field might be oscillating up and down, while the magnetic field oscillates right and left.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] This picture can be rotated with the electric field oscillating right and left and the magnetic field oscillating down and up.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] This is a different solution that is traveling in the same direction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] This arbitrariness in the orientation with respect to propagation direction is known as polarization.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] On a quantum level, it is described as photon polarization.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] The direction of the polarization is defined as the direction of the electric field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] More general forms of the second-order wave equations given above are available, allowing for both non-vacuum propagation media and sources.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] Many competing derivations exist, all with varying levels of approximation and intended applications.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] One very general example is a form of the electric field equation, which was factorized into a pair of explicitly directional wave equations, and then efficiently reduced into a single uni-directional wave equation by means of a simple slow-evolution approximation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In atomic physics and quantum chemistry, the **electron configuration** is the distribution of electrons of an atom or molecule (or other physical structure) in atomic or molecular orbitals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, the electron configuration of the neon atom is 1s2 2s2 2p6, meaning that the 1s, 2s, and 2p subshells are occupied by two, two, and six electrons, respectively.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Electronic configurations describe each electron as moving independently in an orbital, in an average field created by the nuclei and all the other electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Mathematically, configurations are described by Slater determinants or configuration state functions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] According to the laws of quantum mechanics, a level of energy is associated with each electron configuration.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In certain conditions, electrons are able to move from one configuration to another by the emission or absorption of a quantum of energy, in the form of a photon.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Knowledge of the electron configuration of different atoms is useful in understanding the structure of the periodic table of elements, for describing the chemical bonds that hold atoms together, and in understanding the chemical formulas of compounds and the geometries of molecules.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In bulk materials, this same idea helps explain the peculiar properties of lasers and semiconductors.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Electron configuration was first conceived under the Bohr model of the atom, and it is still common to speak of shells and subshells despite the advances in understanding of the quantum-mechanical nature of electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] An electron shell is the set of allowed states that share the same principal quantum number, *n*, that electrons may occupy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In each term of an electron configuration, *n* is the positive integer that precedes each orbital letter (e.g. helium's electron configuration is 1s2, therefore *n* = 1, and the orbital contains two electrons).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] An atom's *n*th electron shell can accommodate 2*n*2 electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, the first shell can accommodate two electrons, the second shell eight electrons, the third shell eighteen, and so on.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The factor of two arises due to electron spin.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Each atomic orbital admits up to two otherwise identical electrons with opposite spin, one with a spin +1⁄2 (usually denoted by an up-arrow) and one with a spin of −1⁄2 (with a down-arrow).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] A subshell is the set of states defined by a common azimuthal quantum number, l, within a shell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The value of l is in the range from 0 to *n* − 1.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The values l = 0, 1, 2, 3 correspond to the s, p, d, and f labels, respectively.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, the 3d subshell has *n* = 3 and l = 2.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The maximum number of electrons that can be placed in a subshell is given by 2(2l + 1).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This gives two electrons in an s subshell, six electrons in a p subshell, and ten electrons in a d subshell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The numbers of electrons that can occupy each shell and each subshell arise from the equations of quantum mechanics, in particular the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that no two electrons in the same atom can have the same values of the four quantum numbers.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Exhaustive technical details about the complete quantum mechanical theory of atomic spectra and structure can be found and studied in the basic book of Robert D.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Physicists and chemists use a standard notation to indicate the electron configurations of atoms and molecules.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For atoms, the notation consists of a sequence of atomic subshell labels (e.g. for phosphorus the sequence 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p) with the number of electrons assigned to each subshell placed as a superscript.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, hydrogen has one electron in the s-orbital of the first shell, so its configuration is written 1s1.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Lithium has two electrons in the 1s-subshell and one in the (higher-energy) 2s-subshell, so its configuration is written 1s2 2s1 (pronounced "one-s-two, two-s-one").
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Phosphorus (atomic number 15) is as follows: 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p3.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] It is quite common to see the letters of the orbital labels (s, p, d, f) written in an italic or slanting typeface, although the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) recommends a normal typeface (as used here).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] After f, the sequence continues alphabetically g, h, i...
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] (l = 4, 5, 6...), skipping j, although orbitals of these types are rarely required.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The electron configurations of molecules are written in a similar way, except that molecular orbital labels are used instead of atomic orbital labels.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For atoms with many electrons, this notation can become lengthy and so an abbreviated notation is used.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The electron configuration can be visualized as the core electrons, equivalent to the noble gas of the preceding period, and the valence electrons: each element in a period differs only by the last few subshells.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Phosphorus, for instance, is in the third period.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] It differs from the second-period neon, whose configuration is 1s2 2s2 2p6, only by the presence of a third shell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The portion of its configuration that is equivalent to neon is abbreviated as [Ne], allowing the configuration of phosphorus to be written as [Ne] 3s2 3p3 rather than writing out the details of the configuration of neon explicitly.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This convention is useful as it is the electrons in the outermost shell that most determine the chemistry of the element.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For a given configuration, the order of writing the orbitals is not completely fixed since only the orbital occupancies have physical significance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, the electron configuration of the titanium ground state can be written as either [Ar] 4s2 3d2 or [Ar] 3d2 4s2.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The first notation follows the order based on the Madelung rule for the configurations of neutral atoms; 4s is filled before 3d in the sequence Ar, K, Ca, Sc, Ti.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The superscript 1 for a singly occupied subshell is not compulsory; for example, aluminium may be written as either [Ne] 3s2 3p1 or [Ne] 3s2 3p.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In atoms where a subshell is unoccupied despite higher subshells being occupied (as is the case in some ions, as well as certain neutral atoms shown to deviate from the Madelung rule), the empty subshell is either denoted with a superscript 0 or left out altogether.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, neutral palladium may be written as either [Kr] 4d10 5s0 or simply [Kr] 4d10, and the lanthanum(III) ion may be written as either [Xe] 4f0 or simply [Xe].
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The energy associated to an electron is that of its orbital.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The energy of a configuration is often approximated as the sum of the energy of each electron, neglecting the electron-electron interactions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The configuration that corresponds to the lowest electronic energy is called the ground state.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Any other configuration is an excited state.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] As an example, the ground state configuration of the sodium atom is 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s1, as deduced from the Aufbau principle (see below).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The first excited state is obtained by promoting a 3s electron to the 3p subshell, to obtain the 1s2 2s2 2p6 3p1 configuration, abbreviated as the 3p level.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Atoms can move from one configuration to another by absorbing or emitting energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In a sodium-vapor lamp for example, sodium atoms are excited to the 3p level by an electrical discharge, and return to the ground state by emitting yellow light of wavelength 589 nm.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Usually, the excitation of valence electrons (such as 3s for sodium) involves energies corresponding to photons of visible or ultraviolet light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The excitation of core electrons is possible, but requires much higher energies, generally corresponding to X-ray photons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This would be the case for example to excite a 2p electron of sodium to the 3s level and form the excited 1s2 2s2 2p5 3s2 configuration.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The remainder of this article deals only with the ground-state configuration, often referred to as "the" configuration of an atom or molecule.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Irving Langmuir was the first to propose in his 1919 article "The Arrangement of Electrons in Atoms and Molecules" in which, building on Gilbert N.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Lewis's cubical atom theory and Walther Kossel's chemical bonding theory, he outlined his "concentric theory of atomic structure".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Langmuir had developed his work on electron atomic structure from other chemists as is shown in the development of the History of the periodic table and the Octet rule.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Niels Bohr (1923) incorporated Langmuir's model that the periodicity in the properties of the elements might be explained by the electronic structure of the atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] His proposals were based on the then current Bohr model of the atom, in which the electron shells were orbits at a fixed distance from the nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Bohr's original configurations would seem strange to a present-day chemist: sulfur was given as 2.4.4.6 instead of 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p4 (2.8.6).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Bohr used 4 and 6 following Alfred Werner's 1893 paper.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In fact, the chemists accepted the concept of atoms long before the physicists.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The valence electrons in the atom were described by Richard Abegg in 1904.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Stoner incorporated Sommerfeld's third quantum number into the description of electron shells, and correctly predicted the shell structure of sulfur to be 2.8.6.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] However neither Bohr's system nor Stoner's could correctly describe the changes in atomic spectra in a magnetic field (the Zeeman effect).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Bohr was well aware of this shortcoming (and others), and had written to his friend Wolfgang Pauli in 1923 to ask for his help in saving quantum theory (the system now known as "old quantum theory").
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Pauli hypothesized successfully that the Zeeman effect can be explained as depending only on the response of the outermost (i.e., valence) electrons of the atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The Schrödinger equation, published in 1926, gave three of the four quantum numbers as a direct consequence of its solution for the hydrogen atom: this solution yields the atomic orbitals that are shown today in textbooks of chemistry (and above).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The examination of atomic spectra allowed the electron configurations of atoms to be determined experimentally, and led to an empirical rule (known as Madelung's rule (1936), see below) for the order in which atomic orbitals are filled with electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The aufbau principle (from the German *Aufbau*, "building up, construction") was an important part of Bohr's original concept of electron configuration.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] a maximum of two electrons are put into orbitals in the order of increasing orbital energy: the lowest-energy subshells are filled before electrons are placed in higher-energy orbitals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The principle works very well (for the ground states of the atoms) for the known 118 elements, although it is sometimes slightly wrong.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The modern form of the aufbau principle describes an order of orbital energies given by Madelung's rule (or Klechkowski's rule).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This rule was first stated by Charles Janet in 1929, rediscovered by Erwin Madelung in 1936, and later given a theoretical justification by V.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Where two subshells have the same value of *n* + l, they are filled in order of increasing *n*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In this list the subshells in parentheses are not occupied in the ground state of the heaviest atom now known (Og, *Z* = 118).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The aufbau principle can be applied, in a modified form, to the protons and neutrons in the atomic nucleus, as in the shell model of nuclear physics and nuclear chemistry.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The form of the periodic table is closely related to the atomic electron configuration for each element.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, all the elements of group 2 (the table's second column) have an electron configuration of [E] *n*s2 (where [E] is a noble gas configuration), and have notable similarities in their chemical properties.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The periodicity of the periodic table in terms of periodic table blocks is due to the number of electrons (2, 6, 10, and 14) needed to fill s, p, d, and f subshells.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] These blocks appear as the rectangular sections of the periodic table.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The electrons in the valence (outermost) shell largely determine each element's chemical properties.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The similarities in the chemical properties were remarked on more than a century before the idea of electron configuration.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The aufbau principle rests on a fundamental postulate that the order of orbital energies is fixed, both for a given element and between different elements; in both cases this is only approximately true.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] It considers atomic orbitals as "boxes" of fixed energy into which can be placed two electrons and no more.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] However, the energy of an electron "in" an atomic orbital depends on the energies of all the other electrons of the atom (or ion, or molecule, etc.).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] There are no "one-electron solutions" for systems of more than one electron, only a set of many-electron solutions that cannot be calculated exactly (although there are mathematical approximations available, such as the Hartree–Fock method).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The fact that the aufbau principle is based on an approximation can be seen from the fact that there is an almost-fixed filling order at all, that, within a given shell, the s-orbital is always filled before the p-orbitals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In a hydrogen-like atom, which only has one electron, calculations indicate that the s-orbital and the p-orbitals of the same shell have exactly the same energy, which in reality is a very good approximation in the absence of external electromagnetic fields.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The naïve application of the aufbau principle leads to a well-known paradox (or apparent paradox) in the basic chemistry of the transition metals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Potassium and calcium appear in the periodic table before the transition metals, and have electron configurations [Ar] 4s1 and [Ar] 4s2 respectively, i.e. the 4s-orbital is filled before the 3d-orbital.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This is in line with Madelung's rule, as the 4s-orbital has *n* + l = 4 (*n* = 4, l = 0) while the 3d-orbital has *n* + l = 5 (*n* = 3, l = 2).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] After calcium, most neutral atoms in the first series of transition metals (scandium through zinc) have configurations with two 4s electrons, but there are two exceptions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Chromium and copper have electron configurations [Ar] 3d5 4s1 and [Ar] 3d10 4s1 respectively, i.e. one electron has passed from the 4s-orbital to a 3d-orbital to generate a half-filled or filled subshell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In this case, the usual explanation is that "half-filled or completely filled subshells are particularly stable arrangements of electrons".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] However, this is not supported by the facts, as tungsten (W) has a Madelung-following d4 s2 configuration and not d5 s1, and niobium (Nb) has an anomalous d4 s1 configuration that does not give it a half-filled or completely filled subshell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The apparent paradox arises when electrons are *removed* from the transition metal atoms to form ions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The first electrons to be ionized come not from the 3d-orbital, as one would expect if it were "higher in energy", but from the 4s-orbital.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This interchange of electrons between 4s and 3d is found for all atoms of the first series of transition metals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The configurations of the neutral atoms (K, Ca, Sc, Ti, V, Cr, ...) usually follow the order 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, ...; however the successive stages of ionization of a given atom (such as Fe4+, Fe3+, Fe2+, Fe+, Fe) usually follow the order 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 3d, 4s, ...
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This phenomenon is only paradoxical if it is assumed that the energy order of atomic orbitals is fixed and unaffected by the nuclear charge or by the presence of electrons in other orbitals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] If that were the case, the 3d-orbital would have the same energy as the 3p-orbital, as it does in hydrogen, yet it clearly does not.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] There is no special reason why the Fe2+ ion should have the same electron configuration as the chromium atom, given that iron has two more protons in its nucleus than chromium, and that the chemistry of the two species is very different.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Melrose and Eric Scerri have analyzed the changes of orbital energy with orbital occupations in terms of the two-electron repulsion integrals of the Hartree–Fock method of atomic structure calculation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] More recently Scerri has argued that contrary to what is stated in the vast majority of sources including the title of his previous article on the subject, 3d orbitals rather than 4s are in fact preferentially occupied.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In chemical environments, configurations can change even more: Th3+ as a bare ion has a configuration of [Rn] 5f1, yet in most ThIII compounds the thorium atom has a 6d1 configuration instead.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Mostly, what is present is rather a superposition of various configurations.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For instance, copper metal is poorly described by either an [Ar] 3d10 4s1 or an [Ar] 3d9 4s2 configuration, but is rather well described as a 90% contribution of the first and a 10% contribution of the second.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Indeed, visible light is already enough to excite electrons in most transition metals, and they often continuously "flow" through different configurations when that happens (copper and its group are an exception).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Similar ion-like 3d*x* 4s0 configurations occur in transition metal complexes as described by the simple crystal field theory, even if the metal has oxidation state 0.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, chromium hexacarbonyl can be described as a chromium atom (not ion) surrounded by six carbon monoxide ligands.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The electron configuration of the central chromium atom is described as 3d6 with the six electrons filling the three lower-energy d orbitals between the ligands.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The other two d orbitals are at higher energy due to the crystal field of the ligands.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This picture is consistent with the experimental fact that the complex is diamagnetic, meaning that it has no unpaired electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] However, in a more accurate description using molecular orbital theory, the d-like orbitals occupied by the six electrons are no longer identical with the d orbitals of the free atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] There are several more exceptions to Madelung's rule among the heavier elements, and as atomic number increases it becomes more and more difficult to find simple explanations such as the stability of half-filled subshells.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] It is possible to predict most of the exceptions by Hartree–Fock calculations, which are an approximate method for taking account of the effect of the other electrons on orbital energies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Qualitatively, for example, the 4d elements have the greatest concentration of Madelung anomalies, because the 4d–5s gap is larger than the 3d–4s and 5d–6s gaps.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For the heavier elements, it is also necessary to take account of the effects of special relativity on the energies of the atomic orbitals, as the inner-shell electrons are moving at speeds approaching the speed of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In general, these relativistic effects tend to decrease the energy of the s-orbitals in relation to the other atomic orbitals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This is the reason why the 6d elements are predicted to have no Madelung anomalies apart from lawrencium (for which relativistic effects stabilise the p1/2 orbital as well and cause its occupancy in the ground state), as relativity intervenes to make the 7s orbitals lower in energy than the 6d ones.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The table below shows the configurations of the f-block (green) and d-block (blue) atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] It shows the ground state configuration in terms of orbital occupancy, but it does not show the ground state in terms of the sequence of orbital energies as determined spectroscopically.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For example, in the transition metals, the 4s orbital is of a higher energy than the 3d orbitals; and in the lanthanides, the 6s is higher than the 4f and 5d.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The ground states can be seen in the Electron configurations of the elements (data page).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] However this also depends on the charge: a calcium atom has 4s lower in energy than 3d, but a Ca2+ cation has 3d lower in energy than 4s.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In practice the configurations predicted by the Madelung rule are at least close to the ground state even in these anomalous cases.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The empty f orbitals in lanthanum, actinium, and thorium contribute to chemical bonding, as do the empty p orbitals in transition metals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Vacant s, d, and f orbitals have been shown explicitly, as is occasionally done, to emphasise the filling order and to clarify that even orbitals unoccupied in the ground state (e.g. lanthanum 4f or palladium 5s) may be occupied and bonding in chemical compounds.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The various anomalies describe the free atoms and do not necessarily predict chemical behavior.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Thus for example neodymium typically forms the +3 oxidation state, despite its configuration [Xe] 4f4 5d0 6s2 that if interpreted naïvely would suggest a more stable +2 oxidation state corresponding to losing only the 6s electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Contrariwise, uranium as [Rn] 5f3 6d1 7s2 is not very stable in the +3 oxidation state either, preferring +4 and +6.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The electron-shell configuration of elements beyond hassium has not yet been empirically verified, but they are expected to follow Madelung's rule without exceptions until element 120.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Element 121 should have the anomalous configuration [Og] 8s2 5g0 6f0 7d0 8p1, having a p rather than a g electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Electron configurations beyond this are tentative and predictions differ between models, but Madelung's rule is expected to break down due to the closeness in energy of the 5g, 6f, 7d, and 8p1/2 orbitals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] That said, the filling sequence 8s, 5g, 6f, 7d, 8p is predicted to hold approximately, with perturbations due to the huge spin-orbit splitting of the 8p and 9p shells, and the huge relativistic stabilisation of the 9s shell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In the context of atomic orbitals, an **open shell** is a valence shell which is not completely filled with electrons or that has not given all of its valence electrons through chemical bonds with other atoms or molecules during a chemical reaction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Conversely a **closed shell** is obtained with a completely filled valence shell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For molecules, "open shell" signifies that there are unpaired electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In molecular orbital theory, this leads to molecular orbitals that are singly occupied.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In computational chemistry implementations of molecular orbital theory, open-shell molecules have to be handled by either the restricted open-shell Hartree–Fock method or the unrestricted Hartree–Fock method.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Conversely a closed-shell configuration corresponds to a state where all molecular orbitals are either doubly occupied or empty (a singlet state).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Open shell molecules are more difficult to study computationally.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Every system has the tendency to acquire the state of stability or a state of minimum energy, and so chemical elements take part in chemical reactions to acquire a stable electronic configuration similar to that of its nearest noble gas.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] An example of this tendency is two hydrogen (H) atoms reacting with one oxygen (O) atom to form water (H2O).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Neutral atomic hydrogen has one electron in its valence shell, and on formation of water it acquires a share of a second electron coming from oxygen, so that its configuration is similar to that of its nearest noble gas helium (He) with two electrons in its valence shell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Similarly, neutral atomic oxygen has six electrons in its valence shell, and acquires a share of two electrons from the two hydrogen atoms, so that its configuration is similar to that of its nearest noble gas neon with eight electrons in its valence shell.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The electronic configuration of polyatomic molecules can change without absorption or emission of a photon through vibronic couplings.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In a solid, the electron states become very numerous.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] They cease to be discrete, and effectively blend into continuous ranges of possible states (an electron band).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The notion of electron configuration ceases to be relevant, and yields to band theory.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The most widespread application of electron configurations is in the rationalization of chemical properties, in both inorganic and organic chemistry.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In effect, electron configurations, along with some simplified forms of molecular orbital theory, have become the modern equivalent of the valence concept, describing the number and type of chemical bonds that an atom can be expected to form.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] This approach is taken further in computational chemistry, which typically attempts to make quantitative estimates of chemical properties.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For many years, most such calculations relied upon the "linear combination of atomic orbitals" (LCAO) approximation, using an ever-larger and more complex basis set of atomic orbitals as the starting point.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] The last step in such a calculation is the assignment of electrons among the molecular orbitals according to the aufbau principle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Not all methods in computational chemistry rely on electron configuration: density functional theory (DFT) is an important example of a method that discards the model.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] For atoms or molecules with more than one electron, the motion of electrons are correlated and such a picture is no longer exact.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] A very large number of electronic configurations are needed to exactly describe any multi-electron system, and precisely associating a certain energy level with any single configuration is not possible.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] However, the electronic wave function is usually dominated by a very small number of configurations and therefore the notion of electronic configuration remains essential for multi-electron systems.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] A fundamental application of electron configurations is in the interpretation of atomic spectra.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] In this case, it is necessary to supplement the electron configuration with one or more term symbols, which describe the different energy levels available to an atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] Term symbols can be calculated for any electron configuration, not just the ground-state configuration listed in tables, although not all the energy levels are observed in practice.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-configuration] It is through the analysis of atomic spectra that the ground-state electron configurations of the elements were experimentally determined.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The **electron** (**e−**, or **β−** in nuclear reactions) is a subatomic particle whose electric charge is negative one elementary charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] It is an elementary particle that comprises the ordinary matter that makes up the universe, along with up and down quarks.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons are extremely lightweight particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In atoms, an electron's matter wave occupies atomic orbitals around a positively charged atomic nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The configuration and energy levels of an atom's electrons determine the atom's chemical properties.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons are bound to the nucleus to different degrees.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The outermost or valence electrons are the least tightly bound and are responsible for the formation of chemical bonds between atoms to create molecules and crystals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] These valence electrons also facilitate all types of chemical reactions by being transferred or shared between atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The inner electron shells make up the atomic core.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The concept of electrons explains numerous physical phenomena.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In metals, the outermost electrons are delocalised and able to move freely, accounting for the high electrical and thermal conductivity of metals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In semiconductors, the number of mobile charge carriers (electrons and holes) can be finely tuned by doping, temperature, voltage and radiation – the basis of modern electronics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] As particle beams in a vacuum, free electrons can be accelerated, focused, and used for applications such as cathode ray tubes, electron microscopes, electron beam welding, lithography, and particle accelerators that generate synchrotron radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons belong to the first generation of the lepton particle family, elementary particles that do not feel the strong nuclear force, and only interact through the weak and electromagnetic forces.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons are generally thought to be elementary particles because they have no known components or substructure.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] An electron's mass is approximately ⁠1/1836⁠ that of a proton.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Quantum mechanical properties of the electron include an intrinsic angular momentum (spin) of half the reduced Planck constant, i.e. ⁠*ħ*/2⁠.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Being fermions, no two electrons can occupy the same quantum state, according to the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Like all elementary particles, electrons exhibit properties of both particles and waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] For example, electrons can collide like particles with other particles and can also be diffracted like light waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The wave properties of electrons are easier to observe with experiments than those of other particles like neutrons and protons because electrons have a lower mass and hence a longer de Broglie wavelength for a given energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The concept of electrons is essential to explain physical phenomena, such as electricity, magnetism, chemistry, and thermal conductivity; they are subject to the forces of gravity, electromagnetism, and the weak interaction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Since an electron has charge, it has a surrounding electric field; if that electron is moving relative to an observer, the observer will observe it to generate a magnetic field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electromagnetic fields produced from other sources will affect the motion of an electron according to the Lorentz force law.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons radiate or absorb energy in the form of photons when they are accelerated.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Laboratory instruments are capable of trapping individual electrons as well as electron plasma by the use of electromagnetic fields.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Special telescopes can detect electron plasma in outer space.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Interactions involving electrons with other subatomic particles are of interest in fields such as chemistry and nuclear physics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Atoms are composed of positive protons within atomic nuclei and the negative electrons without, held together by Coulomb force interaction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Ionization state (differences in the proportions of negative electrons versus positive nuclei) or sharing of the electrons between two or more atoms are the main causes of chemical bonding.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons participate in nuclear reactions, such as nucleosynthesis in stars, where they are known as beta particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons can be created through beta decay of radioactive isotopes and in high-energy collisions, for instance, when cosmic rays enter the atmosphere.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The antiparticle of the electron is called the positron; it is identical to the electron, except that it carries electrical charge of the opposite sign.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When an electron collides with a positron, both particles can be annihilated, producing gamma ray photons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The ancient Greeks noticed that amber attracted small objects when rubbed with fur.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Along with lightning, this phenomenon is one of humanity's earliest recorded experiences with electricity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In his 1600 treatise *De Magnete*, the English scientist William Gilbert coined the Neo-Latin term *electrica*, to refer to those substances with property similar to that of amber which attract small objects after being rubbed.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Both *electric* and *electricity* are derived from the Latin **ēlectrum** (also the root of the alloy of the same name), which came from the Greek word for amber, ἤλεκτρον (**ēlektron**).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In the early 1700s, French chemist Charles François du Fay found that if a charged gold leaf is repulsed by glass rubbed with silk, then the same charged gold leaf is attracted by amber rubbed with wool.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] From this and other results of similar types of experiments, du Fay concluded that electricity consists of two electrical fluids, *vitreous* fluid from glass rubbed with silk and *resinous* fluid from amber rubbed with wool.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] These two fluids can neutralize each other when combined.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] American scientist Ebenezer Kinnersley later also independently reached the same conclusion.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] A decade later Benjamin Franklin proposed that electricity was not from different types of electrical fluid, but a single electrical fluid showing an excess (+) or deficit (−).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] He gave them the modern charge nomenclature of positive and negative respectively.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Franklin thought of the charge carrier as being positive, but he did not correctly identify which situation was a surplus of the charge carrier, and which situation was a deficit.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Between 1838 and 1851, British natural philosopher Richard Laming developed the idea that an atom is composed of a core of matter surrounded by subatomic particles that had unit electric charges.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Beginning in 1846, German physicist Wilhelm Eduard Weber theorized that electricity was composed of positively and negatively charged fluids, and their interaction was governed by the inverse square law.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] After studying the phenomenon of electrolysis in 1874, Irish physicist George Johnstone Stoney suggested that there existed a "single definite quantity of electricity", the charge of a monovalent ion.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] He was able to estimate the value of this elementary charge *e* by means of Faraday's laws of electrolysis.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] However, Stoney believed these charges were permanently attached to atoms and could not be removed.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1881, German physicist Hermann von Helmholtz argued that both positive and negative charges were divided into elementary parts, each of which "behaves like atoms of electricity".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Stoney initially coined the term *electrolion* in 1881.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Ten years later, he switched to *electron* to describe these elementary charges, writing in 1894: "... an estimate was made of the actual amount of this most remarkable fundamental unit of electricity, for which I have since ventured to suggest the name *electron*".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] A 1906 proposal to change to *electrion* failed because Hendrik Lorentz preferred to keep *electron*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The word *electron* is a combination of the words *electric* and *ion*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The suffix -*on* which is now used to designate other subatomic particles, such as a proton or neutron, is in turn derived from electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1869, Plücker's student Johann Wilhelm Hittorf found that a solid body placed in between the cathode and the phosphorescence would cast a shadow upon the phosphorescent region of the tube.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Hittorf inferred that there are straight rays emitted from the cathode and that the phosphorescence was caused by the rays striking the tube walls.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Furthermore, he also discovered that these rays are deflected by magnets just like lines of current.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1876, the German physicist Eugen Goldstein showed that the rays were emitted perpendicular to the cathode surface, which distinguished between the rays that were emitted from the cathode and the incandescent light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Decades of experimental and theoretical research involving cathode rays were important in J.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Thomson's eventual discovery of electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Goldstein also experimented with double cathodes and hypothesized that one ray may repulse another, although he didn't believe that any particles might be involved.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] During the 1870s, the English chemist and physicist Sir William Crookes developed the first cathode-ray tube to have a high vacuum inside.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] He then showed in 1874 that the cathode rays can turn a small paddle wheel when placed in their path.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Therefore, he concluded that the rays carried momentum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Furthermore, by applying a magnetic field, he was able to deflect the rays, thereby demonstrating that the beam behaved as though it were negatively charged.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1879, he proposed that these properties could be explained by regarding cathode rays as composed of negatively charged gaseous molecules in a fourth state of matter, in which the mean free path of the particles is so long that collisions may be ignored.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1883, not yet well-known German physicist Heinrich Hertz tried to prove that cathode rays are electrically neutral and got what he interpreted as a confident absence of deflection in electrostatic, as opposed to magnetic, field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Thomson explained in 1897, Hertz placed the deflecting electrodes in a highly conductive area of the tube, resulting in a strong screening effect close to their surface.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The German-born British physicist Arthur Schuster expanded upon Crookes's experiments by placing metal plates parallel to the cathode rays and applying an electric potential between the plates.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The field deflected the rays toward the positively charged plate, providing further evidence that the rays carried negative charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] By measuring the amount of deflection for a given electric and magnetic field, in 1890 Schuster was able to estimate the charge-to-mass ratio of the ray components.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] However, this produced a value that was more than a thousand times greater than what was expected, so little credence was given to his calculations at the time.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This is because it was assumed that the charge carriers were much heavier hydrogen or nitrogen atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Schuster's estimates would subsequently turn out to be largely correct.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1892 Hendrik Lorentz suggested that the mass of these particles (electrons) could be a consequence of their electric charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] While studying naturally fluorescing minerals in 1896, the French physicist Henri Becquerel discovered that they emitted radiation without any exposure to an external energy source.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] These radioactive materials became the subject of much interest for scientists, including the New Zealand physicist Ernest Rutherford who discovered they emitted particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] He designated these particles alpha and beta, on the basis of their ability to penetrate matter.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1900, Becquerel showed that the beta rays emitted by radium could be deflected by an electric field, and that their mass-to-charge ratio was the same as for cathode rays.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This evidence strengthened the view that electrons existed as components of atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Wilson, performed experiments indicating that cathode rays really were unique particles, rather than waves, atoms or molecules as was believed earlier.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] By 1899 he showed that their charge-to-mass ratio, *e*/*m*, was independent of cathode material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] He further showed that the negatively charged particles produced by radioactive materials, by heated materials and by illuminated materials were universal.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Thomson measured *m*/*e* for cathode ray "corpuscles", and made good estimates of the charge *e*, leading to value for the mass *m*, finding a value 1400 times less massive than the least massive ion known: hydrogen.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In the same year Emil Wiechert and Walter Kaufmann also calculated the *e*/*m* ratio but did not take the step of interpreting their results as showing a new particle, while J.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Thomson would subsequently in 1899 give estimates for the electron charge and mass as well: *e* ≈ 6.8×10−10 esu and *m* ≈ 3×10−26 g.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The name "electron" was adopted for these particles by the scientific community, mainly due to the advocation by G.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The term was originally coined by George Johnstone Stoney in 1891 as a tentative name for the basic unit of electrical charge (which had then yet to be discovered).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The electron's charge was more carefully measured by the American physicists Robert Millikan and Harvey Fletcher in their oil-drop experiment of 1909, the results of which were published in 1911.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This experiment used an electric field to prevent a charged droplet of oil from falling as a result of gravity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This device could measure the electric charge from as few as 1–150 ions with an error margin of less than 0.3%.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Comparable experiments had been done earlier by Thomson's team, using clouds of charged water droplets generated by electrolysis, and in 1911 by Abram Ioffe, who independently obtained the same result as Millikan using charged microparticles of metals, then published his results in 1913.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] However, oil drops were more stable than water drops because of their slower evaporation rate, and thus more suited to precise experimentation over longer periods of time.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Around the beginning of the twentieth century, it was found that under certain conditions a fast-moving charged particle caused a condensation of supersaturated water vapor along its path.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1911, Charles Wilson used this principle to devise his cloud chamber so he could photograph the tracks of charged particles, such as fast-moving electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] By 1914, experiments by physicists Ernest Rutherford, Henry Moseley, James Franck and Gustav Hertz had largely established the structure of an atom as a dense nucleus of positive charge surrounded by lower-mass electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1913, Danish physicist Niels Bohr postulated that electrons resided in quantized energy states, with their energies determined by the angular momentum of the electron's orbit about the nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The electrons could move between those states, or orbits, by the emission or absorption of photons of specific frequencies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] By means of these quantized orbits, he accurately explained the spectral lines of the hydrogen atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] However, Bohr's model failed to account for the relative intensities of the spectral lines and it was unsuccessful in explaining the spectra of more complex atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Chemical bonds between atoms were explained by Gilbert Newton Lewis, who in 1916 proposed that a covalent bond between two atoms is maintained by a pair of electrons shared between them.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Later, in 1927, Walter Heitler and Fritz London gave the full explanation of the electron-pair formation and chemical bonding in terms of quantum mechanics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1919, the American chemist Irving Langmuir elaborated on the Lewis's static model of the atom and suggested that all electrons were distributed in successive "concentric (nearly) spherical shells, all of equal thickness".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In turn, he divided the shells into a number of cells each of which contained one pair of electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] With this model Langmuir was able to qualitatively explain the chemical properties of all elements in the periodic table, which were known to largely repeat themselves according to the periodic law.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1924, Austrian physicist Wolfgang Pauli observed that the shell-like structure of the atom could be explained by a set of four parameters that defined every quantum energy state, as long as each state was occupied by no more than a single electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This prohibition against more than one electron occupying the same quantum energy state became known as the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The physical mechanism to explain the fourth parameter, which had two distinct possible values, was provided by the Dutch physicists Samuel Goudsmit and George Uhlenbeck.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1925, they suggested that an electron, in addition to the angular momentum of its orbit, possesses an intrinsic angular momentum and magnetic dipole moment.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This is analogous to the rotation of the Earth on its axis as it orbits the Sun.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The intrinsic angular momentum became known as spin, and explained the previously mysterious splitting of spectral lines observed with a high-resolution spectrograph; this phenomenon is known as fine structure splitting.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In his 1924 dissertation **Recherches sur la théorie des quanta** (Research on Quantum Theory), French physicist Louis de Broglie hypothesized that all matter can be represented as a de Broglie wave in the manner of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] That is, under the appropriate conditions, electrons and other matter would show properties of either particles or waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The corpuscular properties of a particle are demonstrated when it is shown to have a localized position in space along its trajectory at any given moment.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The wave-like nature of light is displayed, for example, when a beam of light is passed through parallel slits thereby creating interference patterns.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Alexander Reid, who was Thomson's graduate student, performed the first experiments but he died soon after in a motorcycle accident and is rarely mentioned.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] De Broglie's prediction of a wave nature for electrons led Erwin Schrödinger to postulate a wave equation for electrons moving under the influence of the nucleus in the atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1926, this equation, the Schrödinger equation, successfully described how electron waves propagated.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Once spin and the interaction between multiple electrons were describable, quantum mechanics made it possible to predict the configuration of electrons in atoms with atomic numbers greater than hydrogen.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1928, building on Wolfgang Pauli's work, Paul Dirac produced a model of the electron – the Dirac equation, consistent with relativity theory, by applying relativistic and symmetry considerations to the hamiltonian formulation of the quantum mechanics of the electromagnetic field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In order to resolve some problems within his relativistic equation, Dirac developed in 1930 a model of the vacuum as an infinite sea of particles with negative energy, later dubbed the Dirac sea.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This led him to predict the existence of a positron, the antimatter counterpart of the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This particle was discovered in 1932 by Carl Anderson, who proposed calling standard electrons *negatrons* and using *electron* as a generic term to describe both the positively and negatively charged variants.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1947, Willis Lamb, working in collaboration with graduate student Robert Retherford, found that certain quantum states of the hydrogen atom, which should have the same energy, were shifted in relation to each other; the difference came to be called the Lamb shift.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] About the same time, Polykarp Kusch, working with Henry M.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Foley, discovered the magnetic moment of the electron is slightly larger than predicted by Dirac's theory.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This small difference was later called anomalous magnetic dipole moment of the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This difference was later explained by the theory of quantum electrodynamics, developed by Sin-Itiro Tomonaga, Julian Schwinger and Richard Feynman in the late 1940s.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] With the development of the particle accelerator during the first half of the twentieth century, physicists began to delve deeper into the properties of subatomic particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The first successful attempt to accelerate electrons using electromagnetic induction was made in 1942 by Donald Kerst.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] His initial betatron reached energies of 2.3 MeV, while subsequent betatrons achieved 300 MeV.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In 1947, synchrotron radiation was discovered with a 70 MeV electron synchrotron at General Electric.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This radiation was caused by the acceleration of electrons through a magnetic field as they moved near the speed of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] With a beam energy of 1.5 GeV, the first high-energy particle collider was ADONE, which began operations in 1968.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This device accelerated electrons and positrons in opposite directions, effectively doubling the energy of their collision when compared to striking a static target with an electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The Large Electron–Positron Collider (LEP) at CERN, which was operational from 1989 to 2000, achieved collision energies of 209 GeV and made important measurements for the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Individual electrons can now be easily confined in ultra small (*L* = 20 nm, *W* = 20 nm) CMOS transistors operated at cryogenic temperature over a range of about 4 K (−269 °C) to 15 K (−258 °C).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The electron wavefunction spreads in a semiconductor lattice and negligibly interacts with the valence band electrons, so it can be treated in the single particle formalism, by replacing its mass with the effective-mass tensor.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In the Standard Model of particle physics, electrons belong to the group of subatomic particles called leptons, which are believed to be fundamental or elementary particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons have the lowest mass of any charged lepton (or electrically charged particle of any type) and belong to the first generation of fundamental particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The second and third generation contain charged leptons, the muon and the tau, which are identical to the electron in charge, spin and interactions, but are more massive.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Leptons differ from the other basic constituent of matter, the quarks, by their lack of strong interaction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] All members of the lepton group are fermions because they all have half-odd integer spin; the electron has spin ⁠*ħ*/2⁠.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The invariant mass of an electron is approximately 9.109×10−31 kg, or 5.486×10−4 Da.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Due to mass–energy equivalence, this corresponds to a rest energy of 8.19×10−14 J (0.511 MeV).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The ratio between the mass of a proton and that of an electron is about 1836.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Astronomical measurements show that the proton-to-electron mass ratio has held the same value, as is predicted by the Standard Model, for at least half the age of the universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons have an electric charge of −1.602176634×10−19 C, which is used as a standard unit of charge for subatomic particles, and is also called the elementary charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Within the limits of experimental accuracy, the electron charge is identical to the charge of a proton, but with the opposite sign.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The electron is commonly symbolized by e− to indicate its negative charge (an electron's anti-particle, the positron, is symbolized by e+ to indicate its identical but positive charge).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The electron has an intrinsic angular momentum or spin of ⁠*ħ*/2⁠.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This property is usually stated by referring to the electron as a spin-1/2 particle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] For such particles the spin magnitude is ⁠*ħ*/2⁠, while the result of the measurement of a projection of the spin on any axis can only be ±⁠*ħ*/2⁠.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In addition to spin, the electron has an intrinsic magnetic moment along its spin axis.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] It is approximately equal to one Bohr magneton, which is a physical constant that is equal to 9.2740100657(29)×10−24 J⋅T−1.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The orientation of the spin with respect to the momentum of the electron defines the property of elementary particles known as helicity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Nevertheless, in condensed matter physics, spin–charge separation can occur in some materials.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In such cases, electrons 'split' into three independent particles, the spinon, the orbiton and the holon (or chargon).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The electron can always be theoretically considered as a bound state of the three, with the spinon carrying the spin of the electron, the orbiton carrying the orbital degree of freedom and the chargon carrying the charge, but in certain conditions they can behave as independent quasiparticles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electron–electron scattering shows no deviation from Coulomb's law: experimentally the electron is structureless and point-like.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Observation of a single electron in a Penning trap suggests the upper limit of the particle's radius to be 10−22 m.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The upper bound of the electron radius of 10−18 m can be derived using the uncertainty relation in energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Theoretical concepts of the electron size are ambiguous.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In relativistic quantum mechanics, the Dirac equation treats the electron as a point charge, but the equivalent Newton–Wigner form does not.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In quantum field theory mathematical treatments of self-energy involve a minimal distance cutoff or equivalent energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Shorter distances (high energies) involve adding more terms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Attempts to create non-quantum mechanical, non-point models lead to contradictions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] For example, a mechanically spinning electron with the classical electron radius and the observed gyromagnetic ratio of the electron would have a tangential velocity exceeding the speed of light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The classical electron radius, with the much larger value of 2.8179×10−15 m (greater than the radius of the proton), is used as a physical constant but is not a measure of the fundamental structure of the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Within the Standard Model of particle physics, the electron is considered stable.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The electron is the least massive known particle with non-zero electric charge: assuming conservation of energy, its decay would violate charge conservation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Many experiment efforts have looked for failures of the Standard Model and of charge conservation by looking for electron decay.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The experimental lower bound for the electron's mean lifetime is 6.6×1028 years, at a 90% confidence level.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] As with all particles, electrons can act as waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This is called the wave–particle duality and can be demonstrated using the double-slit experiment.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The wave-like nature of the electron allows it to pass through two parallel slits simultaneously, rather than just one slit as would be the case for a classical particle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In quantum mechanics, the wave-like property of one particle can be described mathematically as a complex-valued function, the wave function, commonly denoted by the Greek letter psi (*ψ*).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When the absolute value of this function is squared, it gives the probability that a particle will be observed near a location—a probability density.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons are identical particles because they cannot be distinguished from each other by their intrinsic physical properties.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In quantum mechanics, this means that a pair of interacting electrons must be able to swap positions without an observable change to the state of the system.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The wave function of fermions, including electrons, is antisymmetric, meaning that it changes sign when two electrons are swapped; that is, *ψ*(*r*1, *r*2) = −*ψ*(*r*2, *r*1), where the variables *r*1 and *r*2 correspond to the first and second electrons, respectively.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Since the absolute value is not changed by a sign swap, this corresponds to equal probabilities.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Bosons, such as the photon, have symmetric wave functions instead.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In the case of antisymmetry, solutions of the wave equation for interacting electrons result in a zero probability that each pair will occupy the same location or state.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This is responsible for the Pauli exclusion principle, which precludes any two electrons from occupying the same quantum state.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This principle explains many of the properties of electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] For example, it causes groups of bound electrons to occupy different orbitals in an atom, rather than all overlapping each other in the same orbit.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In a simplified picture, which often tends to give the wrong idea but may serve to illustrate some aspects, every photon spends some time as a combination of a virtual electron plus its antiparticle, the virtual positron, which rapidly annihilate each other shortly thereafter.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The combination of the energy variation needed to create these particles, and the time during which they exist, fall under the threshold of detectability expressed by the Heisenberg uncertainty relation, Δ*E* · Δ*t* ≥ *ħ*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In effect, the energy needed to create these virtual particles, Δ*E*, can be "borrowed" from the vacuum for a period of time, Δ*t*, so that their product is no more than the reduced Planck constant, *ħ* ≈ 6.6×10−16 eV·s.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Thus, for a virtual electron, Δ*t* is at most 1.3×10−21 s.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] While an electron–positron virtual pair is in existence, the Coulomb force from the ambient electric field surrounding an electron causes a created positron to be attracted to the original electron, while a created electron experiences a repulsion.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This causes what is called vacuum polarization.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In effect, the vacuum behaves like a medium having a dielectric permittivity more than unity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Thus the effective charge of an electron is actually smaller than its true value, and the charge decreases with increasing distance from the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This polarization was confirmed experimentally in 1997 using the Japanese TRISTAN particle accelerator.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Virtual particles cause a comparable shielding effect for the mass of the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The interaction with virtual particles also explains the small (about 0.1%) deviation of the intrinsic magnetic moment of the electron from the Bohr magneton (the anomalous magnetic moment).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The extraordinarily precise agreement of this predicted difference with the experimentally determined value is viewed as one of the great achievements of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The apparent paradox in classical physics of a point particle electron having intrinsic angular momentum and magnetic moment can be explained by the formation of virtual photons in the electric field generated by the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] These photons can heuristically be thought of as causing the electron to shift about in a jittery fashion (known as zitterbewegung), which results in a net circular motion with precession.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This motion produces both the spin and the magnetic moment of the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In atoms, this creation of virtual photons explains the Lamb shift observed in spectral lines.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The Compton Wavelength shows that near elementary particles such as the electron, the uncertainty of the energy allows for the creation of virtual particles near the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This wavelength explains the "static" of virtual particles around elementary particles at a close distance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] An electron generates an electric field that exerts an attractive force on a particle with a positive charge, such as the proton, and a repulsive force on a particle with a negative charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The strength of this force in nonrelativistic approximation is determined by Coulomb's inverse square law.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When an electron is in motion, it generates a magnetic field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The Ampère–Maxwell law relates the magnetic field to the mass motion of electrons (the current) with respect to an observer.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This property of induction supplies the magnetic field that drives an electric motor.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The electromagnetic field of an arbitrary moving charged particle is expressed by the Liénard–Wiechert potentials, which are valid even when the particle's speed is close to that of light (relativistic).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When an electron is moving through a magnetic field, it is subject to the Lorentz force that acts perpendicularly to the plane defined by the magnetic field and the electron velocity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This centripetal force causes the electron to follow a helical trajectory through the field at a radius called the gyroradius.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The acceleration from this curving motion induces the electron to radiate energy in the form of synchrotron radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The energy emission in turn causes a recoil of the electron, known as the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac Force, which creates a friction that slows the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This force is caused by a back-reaction of the electron's own field upon itself.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Photons mediate electromagnetic interactions between particles in quantum electrodynamics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] An isolated electron at a constant velocity cannot emit or absorb a real photon; doing so would violate conservation of energy and momentum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Instead, virtual photons can transfer momentum between two charged particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This exchange of virtual photons, for example, generates the Coulomb force.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Energy emission can occur when a moving electron is deflected by a charged particle, such as a proton.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The deceleration of the electron results in the emission of Bremsstrahlung radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] An inelastic collision between a photon (light) and a solitary (free) electron is called Compton scattering.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This collision results in a transfer of momentum and energy between the particles, which modifies the wavelength of the photon by an amount called the Compton shift.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The maximum magnitude of this wavelength shift is *h*/*m*e*c*, which is known as the Compton wavelength.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] For an electron, it has a value of 2.43×10−12 m.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When the wavelength of the light is long (for instance, the wavelength of the visible light is 0.4–0.7 μm) the wavelength shift becomes negligible.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Such interaction between the light and free electrons is called Thomson scattering or linear Thomson scattering.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The relative strength of the electromagnetic interaction between two charged particles, such as an electron and a proton, is given by the fine-structure constant.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This value is a dimensionless quantity formed by the ratio of two energies: the electrostatic energy of attraction (or repulsion) at a separation of one Compton wavelength, and the rest energy of the charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When electrons and positrons collide, they annihilate each other, giving rise to two or more gamma ray photons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] If the electron and positron have negligible momentum, a positronium atom can form before annihilation results in two or three gamma ray photons whose energies total 1.022 MeV.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] On the other hand, a high-energy photon can transform into an electron and a positron by a process called pair production, but only in the presence of a nearby charged particle, such as a nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In the theory of electroweak interaction, the left-handed component of electron's wavefunction forms a weak isospin doublet with the electron neutrino.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This means that during weak interactions, electron neutrinos behave like electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Either member of this doublet can undergo a charged current interaction by emitting or absorbing a W and be converted into the other member.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Charge is conserved during this reaction because the W boson also carries a charge, canceling out any net change during the transmutation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Charged current interactions are responsible for the phenomenon of beta decay in a radioactive atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Both the electron and electron neutrino can undergo a neutral current interaction via a Z0 exchange, and this is responsible for neutrino–electron elastic scattering.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] An electron can be *bound* to the nucleus of an atom by the attractive Coulomb force.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] A system of one or more electrons bound to a nucleus is called an atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] If the number of electrons is different from the nucleus's electrical charge, such an atom is called an ion.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The wave-like behavior of a bound electron is described by a function called an atomic orbital.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Each orbital has its own set of quantum numbers such as energy, angular momentum, and projection of angular momentum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Only a discrete set of these orbitals exist around the nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] According to the Pauli exclusion principle, each orbital can be occupied by up to two electrons, which must differ in their spin quantum number.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons can transfer between different orbitals by the emission or absorption of photons with an energy that matches the difference in potential between the orbitals.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Other methods of orbital transfer include collisions with particles, such as electrons, and the Auger effect.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] To escape the atom, the energy of the electron must be increased above its binding energy to the atom.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This occurs, for example, with the photoelectric effect, where an incident photon exceeding the atom's ionization energy is absorbed by the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The orbital angular momentum of electrons is quantized.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Because the electron is charged, it produces an orbital magnetic moment that is proportional to the angular momentum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The net magnetic moment of an atom is equal to the vector sum of orbital and spin magnetic moments of all electrons and the nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The magnetic moment of the nucleus is negligible compared with that of the electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The magnetic moments of the electrons that occupy the same orbital, called paired electrons, cancel each other out.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The chemical bond between atoms occurs as a result of electromagnetic interactions, as described by the laws of quantum mechanics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The strongest bonds are formed by the sharing or transfer of electrons between atoms, allowing the formation of molecules.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Within a molecule, electrons move under the influence of several nuclei, and occupy molecular orbitals; much as they can occupy atomic orbitals in isolated atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] A fundamental factor in these molecular structures is the existence of electron pairs.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] These are electrons with opposed spins, allowing them to occupy the same molecular orbital without violating the Pauli exclusion principle (much like in atoms).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Different molecular orbitals have different spatial distribution of the electron density.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] For instance, electrons can be found with the maximal probability in a relatively small volume between the nuclei when in bonded pairs (the pairs that actually bind atoms together).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In contrast, electrons are distributed in a large volume around nuclei in non-bonded pairs.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] An object has a net electric charge if the total negative charge provided by electrons does not equal the positive charge from the nuclei.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When there is an excess of electrons, the object is said to be negatively charged.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When there is a lack of electrons, the object is said to be positively charged.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When the number of electrons and the number of protons are equal, their charges cancel each other and the object is said to be electrically neutral.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] A macroscopic body can develop an electric charge through rubbing, by the triboelectric effect.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Independent electrons moving in vacuum are termed *free* electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons in metals also behave as if they were free.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In reality the particles that are commonly termed electrons in metals and other solids are quasi-electrons – quasiparticles, which have the same electrical charge, spin, and magnetic moment as real electrons but might have a different mass.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When free electrons – both in vacuum and metals – move, they produce a net flow of charge called an electric current, which generates a magnetic field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Likewise a current can be created by a changing magnetic field.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] These interactions are described mathematically by Maxwell's equations.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] At a given temperature, each material has an electrical conductivity that determines the value of electric current when an electric potential is applied.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Examples of good conductors include metals such as copper and gold, whereas glass and Teflon are poor conductors.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In any dielectric material, the electrons remain bound to their respective atoms and the material behaves as an insulator.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Most semiconductors have a variable level of conductivity that lies between the extremes of conduction and insulation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] On the other hand, metals have an electronic band structure containing partially filled electronic bands.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The presence of such bands allows electrons in metals to behave as if they were free or delocalized electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] These electrons are not associated with specific atoms, so when an electric field is applied, they are free to move like a gas (called Fermi gas) through the material much like free electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Because of collisions between electrons and atoms, the drift velocity of electrons in a conductor is on the order of millimeters per second.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] However, the speed at which a change of current at one point in the material causes changes in currents in other parts of the material, the velocity of propagation, is typically about 75% of light speed.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This occurs because electrical signals propagate as a wave, with the velocity dependent on the dielectric constant of the material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Metals make relatively good conductors of heat, primarily because the delocalized electrons are free to transport thermal energy between atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] However, unlike electrical conductivity, the thermal conductivity of a metal is nearly independent of temperature.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This is expressed mathematically by the Wiedemann–Franz law, which states that the ratio of thermal conductivity to the electrical conductivity is proportional to the temperature.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The thermal disorder in the metallic lattice increases the electrical resistivity of the material, producing a temperature dependence for electric current.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] When cooled below a point called the critical temperature, materials can undergo a phase transition in which they lose all resistivity to electric current, in a process known as superconductivity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] In BCS theory, pairs of electrons called Cooper pairs have their motion coupled to nearby matter via lattice vibrations called phonons, thereby avoiding the collisions with atoms that normally create electrical resistance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] (Cooper pairs have a radius of roughly 100 nm, so they can overlap each other.) However, the mechanism by which higher temperature superconductors operate remains uncertain.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Electrons inside conducting solids, which are quasi-particles themselves, when tightly confined at temperatures close to absolute zero, behave as though they had split into three other quasiparticles: spinons, orbitons and holons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The former carries spin and magnetic moment, the next carries its orbital location while the latter electrical charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] According to Einstein's theory of special relativity, as an electron's speed approaches the speed of light, from an observer's point of view its relativistic mass increases, thereby making it more and more difficult to accelerate it with respect to the observer's frame of reference.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The speed of an electron can approach, but never reach, the speed of light in vacuum, *c*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] However, when relativistic electrons—that is, electrons moving at a speed close to *c*—are injected into a dielectric medium such as water, where the local speed of light is significantly less than *c*, the electrons temporarily travel faster than light in the medium.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] As they interact with the medium, they generate a faint light called Cherenkov radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] The effects of special relativity are based on a quantity known as the Lorentz factor, defined as $\textstyle \gamma =1/{\sqrt {1-{v^{2}}/{c^{2}}}}$ , where *v* is the speed of the particle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] For example, the Stanford linear accelerator can accelerate an electron to roughly 51 GeV.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] Since an electron behaves as a wave, at a given velocity it has a characteristic de Broglie wavelength.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] This is given by *λ*e = *h*/*p* where *h* is the Planck constant and *p* is the momentum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p01] For the 51 GeV electron above, the wavelength is about 2.4×10−17 m, small enough to explore structures well below the size of an atomic nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The Big Bang theory is the most widely accepted scientific theory to explain the early stages in the evolution of the Universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] For the first millisecond of the Big Bang, the temperatures were over 10 billion kelvins and photons had mean energies over a million electronvolts.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] These photons were sufficiently energetic that they could react with each other to form pairs of electrons and positrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] An equilibrium between electrons, positrons and photons was maintained during this phase of the evolution of the Universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] After 15 seconds had passed, however, the temperature of the universe dropped below the threshold where electron–positron formation could occur.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Most of the surviving electrons and positrons annihilated each other, releasing gamma radiation that briefly reheated the universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] For reasons that remain uncertain, during the annihilation process there was an excess in the number of particles over antiparticles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Hence, about one electron for every billion electron–positron pairs survived.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] This excess matched the excess of protons over antiprotons, in a condition known as baryon asymmetry, resulting in a net charge of zero for the universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The surviving protons and neutrons began to participate in reactions with each other—in the process known as nucleosynthesis, forming isotopes of hydrogen and helium, with trace amounts of lithium.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] This process peaked after about five minutes.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] For about the next 300000–400000 years, the excess electrons remained too energetic to bind with atomic nuclei.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] What followed is a period known as recombination, when neutral atoms were formed and the expanding universe became transparent to radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Roughly one million years after the big bang, the first generation of stars began to form.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Within a star, stellar nucleosynthesis results in the production of positrons from the fusion of atomic nuclei.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] These antimatter particles immediately annihilate with electrons, releasing gamma rays.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The net result is a steady reduction in the number of electrons, and a matching increase in the number of neutrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] However, the process of stellar evolution can result in the synthesis of radioactive isotopes.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Selected isotopes can subsequently undergo negative beta decay, emitting an electron and antineutrino from the nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] An example is the cobalt-60 (60Co) isotope, which decays to form nickel-60 (60 Ni).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] At the end of its lifetime, a star with more than about 20 solar masses can undergo gravitational collapse to form a black hole.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] According to classical physics, these massive stellar objects exert a gravitational attraction that is strong enough to prevent anything, even electromagnetic radiation, from escaping past the Schwarzschild radius.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] However, quantum mechanical effects are believed to potentially allow the emission of Hawking radiation at this distance.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Electrons (and positrons) are thought to be created at the event horizon of these stellar remnants.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] When a pair of virtual particles (such as an electron and positron) is created in the vicinity of the event horizon, random spatial positioning might result in one of them to appear on the exterior; this process is called quantum tunnelling.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The gravitational potential of the black hole can then supply the energy that transforms this virtual particle into a real particle, allowing it to radiate away into space.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] In exchange, the other member of the pair is given negative energy, which results in a net loss of mass–energy by the black hole.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The rate of Hawking radiation increases with decreasing mass, eventually causing the black hole to evaporate away until, finally, it explodes.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Cosmic rays are particles traveling through space with high energies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Energy events as high as 3.0×1020 eV have been recorded.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] When these particles collide with nucleons in the Earth's atmosphere, a shower of particles is generated, including pions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] More than half of the cosmic radiation observed from the Earth's surface consists of muons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The particle called a muon is a lepton produced in the upper atmosphere by the decay of a pion.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] A muon, in turn, can decay to form an electron or positron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Remote observation of electrons requires detection of their radiated energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] For example, in high-energy environments such as the corona of a star, free electrons form a plasma that radiates energy due to Bremsstrahlung radiation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Electron gas can undergo plasma oscillation, which is waves caused by synchronized variations in electron density, and these produce energy emissions that can be detected by using radio telescopes.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The frequency of a photon is proportional to its energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] As a bound electron transitions between different energy levels of an atom, it absorbs or emits photons at characteristic frequencies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] For instance, when atoms are irradiated by a source with a broad spectrum, distinct dark lines appear in the spectrum of transmitted radiation in places where the corresponding frequency is absorbed by the atom's electrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Each element or molecule displays a characteristic set of spectral lines, such as the hydrogen spectral series.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] When detected, spectroscopic measurements of the strength and width of these lines allow the composition and physical properties of a substance to be determined.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] In laboratory conditions, the interactions of individual electrons can be observed by means of particle detectors, which allow measurement of specific properties such as energy, spin and charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The development of the Paul trap and Penning trap allows charged particles to be contained within a small region for long durations.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] This enables precise measurements of the particle properties.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] For example, in one instance a Penning trap was used to contain a single electron for a period of 10 months.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The magnetic moment of the electron was measured to a precision of eleven digits, which, in 1980, was a greater accuracy than for any other physical constant.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The first video images of an electron's energy distribution were captured by a team at Lund University in Sweden, February 2008.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The scientists used extremely short flashes of light, called attosecond pulses, which allowed an electron's motion to be observed for the first time.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The distribution of the electrons in solid materials can be visualized by angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] This technique employs the photoelectric effect to measure the reciprocal space—a mathematical representation of periodic structures that is used to infer the original structure.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] ARPES can be used to determine the direction, speed and scattering of electrons within the material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] They allow energy densities up to 107 W·cm−2 across a narrow focus diameter of 0.1–1.3 mm and usually require no filler material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] This welding technique must be performed in a vacuum to prevent the electrons from interacting with the gas before reaching their target, and it can be used to join conductive materials that would otherwise be considered unsuitable for welding.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Electron-beam lithography (EBL) is a method of etching semiconductors at resolutions smaller than a micrometer.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] This technique is limited by high costs, slow performance, the need to operate the beam in the vacuum and the tendency of the electrons to scatter in solids.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The last problem limits the resolution to about 10 nm.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] For this reason, EBL is primarily used for the production of small numbers of specialized integrated circuits.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Electron beam processing is used to irradiate materials in order to change their physical properties or sterilize medical and food products.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Electron beams fluidise or quasi-melt glasses without significant increase of temperature on intensive irradiation: e.g. intensive electron radiation causes a many orders of magnitude decrease of viscosity and stepwise decrease of its activation energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Linear particle accelerators generate electron beams for treatment of superficial tumors in radiation therapy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Electron therapy can treat such skin lesions as basal-cell carcinomas because an electron beam only penetrates to a limited depth before being absorbed, typically up to 5 cm for electron energies in the range 5–20 MeV.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] An electron beam can be used to supplement the treatment of areas that have been irradiated by X-rays.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Particle accelerators use electric fields to propel electrons and their antiparticles to high energies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] These particles emit synchrotron radiation as they pass through magnetic fields.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The dependency of the intensity of this radiation upon spin polarizes the electron beam – a process known as the Sokolov–Ternov effect.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Polarized electron beams can be useful for various experiments.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Synchrotron radiation can also cool the electron beams to reduce the momentum spread of the particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Electron and positron beams are collided upon the particles' accelerating to the required energies; particle detectors observe the resulting energy emissions, which particle physics studies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Low-energy electron diffraction (LEED) is a method of bombarding a crystalline material with a collimated beam of electrons and then observing the resulting diffraction patterns to determine the structure of the material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The required energy of the electrons is typically in the range 20–200 eV.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The reflection high-energy electron diffraction (RHEED) technique uses the reflection of a beam of electrons fired at various low angles to characterize the surface of crystalline materials.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The beam energy is typically in the range 8–20 keV and the angle of incidence is 1°–4°.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The electron microscope directs a focused beam of electrons at a specimen.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Some electrons change their properties, such as movement direction, angle, and relative phase and energy as the beam interacts with the material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Microscopists can record these changes in the electron beam to produce atomically resolved images of the material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] In blue light, conventional optical microscopes have a diffraction-limited resolution of about 200 nm.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] By comparison, electron microscopes are limited by the de Broglie wavelength of the electron.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] This wavelength, for example, is equal to 0.0037 nm for electrons accelerated across a 100000 V potential.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The Transmission Electron Aberration-Corrected Microscope is capable of sub-0.05 nm resolution, which is more than enough to resolve individual atoms.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] This capability makes the electron microscope a useful laboratory instrument for high resolution imaging.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] However, electron microscopes are expensive instruments that are costly to maintain.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Two main types of electron microscopes exist: transmission and scanning.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Transmission electron microscopes function like overhead projectors, with a beam of electrons passing through a slice of material then being projected by lenses on a photographic slide or a charge-coupled device.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Scanning electron microscopes rasteri a finely focused electron beam, as in a TV set, across the studied sample to produce the image.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Magnifications range from 100× to 1,000,000× or higher for both microscope types.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The scanning tunneling microscope uses quantum tunneling of electrons from a sharp metal tip into the studied material and can produce atomically resolved images of its surface.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] In the free-electron laser (FEL), a relativistic electron beam passes through a pair of undulators that contain arrays of dipole magnets whose fields point in alternating directions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] The electrons emit synchrotron radiation that coherently interacts with the same electrons to strongly amplify the radiation field at the resonance frequency.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] FEL can emit a coherent high-brilliance electromagnetic radiation with a wide range of frequencies, from microwaves to soft X-rays.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] These devices are used in manufacturing, communication, and in medical applications, such as soft tissue surgery.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Electrons are important in cathode-ray tubes, which have been extensively used as display devices in laboratory instruments, computer monitors and television sets.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] In a photomultiplier tube, every photon striking the photocathode initiates an avalanche of electrons that produces a detectable current pulse.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] Vacuum tubes use the flow of electrons to manipulate electrical signals, and they played a critical role in the development of electronics technology.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electron-p02] However, they have been largely supplanted by solid-state devices such as the transistor.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In physics, an **electronvolt** (symbol **eV**), also written as **electron-volt** and **electron volt**, is a unit of measurement equivalent to the amount of kinetic energy gained by a single electron accelerating through an electric potential difference of one volt in a vacuum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] When used as a unit of energy, the numerical value of 1 eV expressed in unit of joules (symbol J) is equal to the numerical value of the charge of an electron in coulombs (symbol C).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] Under the 2019 revision of the SI, this sets 1 eV equal to the exact value 1.602176634×10−19 J.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] Historically, the electronvolt was devised as a standard unit of measure through its usefulness in electrostatic particle accelerator sciences, because a particle with electric charge *q* gains an energy *E* = *qV* after passing through a voltage of *V*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] An electronvolt is the amount of energy gained or lost by a single electron when it moves through an electric potential difference of one volt.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] Hence, it has a value of one volt, which is 1 J/C, multiplied by the elementary charge *e* = 1.602176634×10−19 C.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] The electronvolt (eV) is a unit of energy, but is not an SI unit.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] It is a commonly used unit of energy within physics, widely used in solid state, atomic, nuclear and particle physics, and high-energy astrophysics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In some older documents, and in the name *Bevatron*, the symbol *BeV* is used, where the *B* stands for *billion*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] The symbol *BeV* is therefore equivalent to *GeV*, though neither is an SI unit.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In the fields of physics in which the electronvolt is used, other quantities are typically measured using units derived from it; products with fundamental constants of importance in the theory are often used.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] By mass–energy equivalence, the electronvolt corresponds to a unit of mass.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] It is common in particle physics, where units of mass and energy are often interchanged, to express mass in units of eV/*c*2, where *c* is the speed of light in vacuum (from *E* = *mc*2).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] It is common to informally express mass in terms of eV as a unit of mass, effectively using a system of natural units with *c* set to 1.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] For example, an electron and a positron, each with a mass of 0.511 MeV/*c*2, can annihilate to yield 1.022 MeV of energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] The atomic mass constant (*m*u), one twelfth of the mass a carbon-12 atom, is close to the mass of a proton.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] By dividing a particle's kinetic energy in electronvolts by the fundamental constant *c* (the speed of light), one can describe the particle's momentum in units of eV/*c*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In natural units in which the fundamental velocity constant *c* is numerically 1, the *c* may informally be omitted to express momentum using the unit electronvolt.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] Dividing a unit of energy (such as eV) by a fundamental constant (such as the speed of light) that has the dimension of velocity (T−1L) facilitates the required conversion for using a unit of energy to quantify momentum.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In particle physics, a system of natural units in which the speed of light in vacuum *c* and the reduced Planck constant *ħ* are dimensionless and equal to unity is widely used: *c* = *ħ* = 1.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In these units, both distances and times are expressed in inverse energy units (while energy and mass are expressed in the same units, see mass–energy equivalence).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In particular, particle scattering lengths are often presented using a unit of inverse particle mass.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] The above relations also allow expressing the mean lifetime *τ* of an unstable particle (in seconds) in terms of its decay width Γ (in eV) via Γ = *ħ*/*τ*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] For example, the B0 meson has a lifetime of 1.530(9) picoseconds, mean decay length is *cτ* = 459.7 μm, or a decay width of 4.302(25)×10−4 eV.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] Conversely, the tiny meson mass differences responsible for meson oscillations are often expressed in the more convenient inverse picoseconds.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In certain fields, such as plasma physics, it is convenient to use the electronvolt to express temperature.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] The *k*B is assumed when using the electronvolt to express temperature, for example, a typical magnetic confinement fusion plasma is 15 keV (kiloelectronvolt), which corresponds to 174 MK (megakelvin).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] Similarly, 1 eV would correspond to an infrared photon of wavelength 1240 nm or frequency 241.8 THz.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] In a low-energy nuclear scattering experiment, it is conventional to refer to the nuclear recoil energy in units of eVr, keVr, etc.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] This distinguishes the nuclear recoil energy from the "electron equivalent" recoil energy (eVee, keVee, etc.) measured by scintillation light.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] For example, the yield of a phototube is measured in phe/keVee (photoelectrons per keV electron-equivalent energy).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] The relationship between eV, eVr, and eVee depends on the medium the scattering takes place in, and must be established empirically for each material.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/electronvolt] One mole of particles given 1 eV of energy each has approximately 96.5 kJ of energy – this corresponds to the Faraday constant (*F* ≈ 96485 C⋅mol−1), where the energy in joules of *n* moles of particles each with energy *E* eV is equal to *E*·*F*·*n*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] In the Standard Model of particle physics, an **elementary particle** or **fundamental particle** is a subatomic particle that is not composed of other particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The Standard Model recognizes seventeen distinct particles—twelve fermions and five bosons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] As a consequence of flavor and color combinations and antimatter, the fermions and bosons are known to have 48 and 13 variations, respectively.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] These 61 elementary particles include electrons and other leptons, quarks, and the fundamental bosons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Subatomic particles such as protons or neutrons, which contain two or more elementary particles, are known as composite particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The concept of an elementary particle is not based on measurements but instead depends on a theoretical framework.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Ordinary matter is composed of atoms, themselves once thought to be indivisible elementary particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The name *atom* comes from the Ancient Greek word *ἄτομος* (atomos) which means *indivisible* or *uncuttable*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Despite the theories about atoms that had existed for thousands of years, their factual existence remained controversial until 1905.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] In that year, Albert Einstein published his paper on Brownian motion, putting to rest theories that had regarded molecules as mathematical illusions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Einstein subsequently identified matter as ultimately composed of various concentrations of energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Subatomic constituents of the atom were first identified toward the end of the 19th century, beginning with the electron, followed by the proton in 1919, the photon in the 1920s, and the neutron in 1932.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] By that time, the advent of quantum mechanics had radically altered the definition of a "particle" by putting forward an understanding in which they carried out a simultaneous existence as matter waves.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Many theoretical elaborations upon, and beyond, the Standard Model have been made since its codification in the 1970s.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] These include notions of supersymmetry, which double the number of elementary particles by hypothesizing that each known particle associates with a "shadow" partner far more massive.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] However, like an additional elementary boson mediating gravitation, such superpartners remain undiscovered as of 2026.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] All elementary particles are either fermions or bosons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] These classes are distinguished by their quantum statistics: fermions obey Fermi–Dirac statistics and bosons obey Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Their spin is differentiated via the spin–statistics theorem: it is half-integer for fermions, and integer for bosons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] In the Standard Model, elementary particles are represented for predictive utility as point particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Though extremely successful, the Standard Model is limited by its omission of gravitation and has some parameters arbitrarily added but unexplained.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] According to the current models of Big Bang nucleosynthesis, the primordial composition of visible matter of the universe should be about 75% hydrogen and 25% helium-4 (in mass).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Neutrons are made of one up and two down quarks, while protons are made of two up and one down quark.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Since the other common elementary particles (such as electrons, neutrinos, or weak bosons) are so light or so rare when compared to atomic nuclei, we can neglect their mass contribution to the observable universe's total mass.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Therefore, one can conclude that most of the visible mass of the universe consists of protons and neutrons, which, like all baryons, in turn consist of up quarks and down quarks.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Some estimates imply that there are roughly 1080 baryons (almost entirely protons and neutrons) in the observable universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The number of protons in the observable universe is called the Eddington number.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] In terms of number of particles, some estimates imply that nearly all the matter, excluding dark matter, occurs in neutrinos, which constitute the majority of the roughly 1086 elementary particles of matter that exist in the visible universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Other estimates imply that roughly 1097 elementary particles exist in the visible universe (not including dark matter), mostly photons and other massless force carriers.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The Standard Model is widely considered to be a provisional theory rather than a truly fundamental one, however, since it is not known if it is compatible with Einstein's general relativity.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] There may be hypothetical elementary particles not described by the Standard Model, such as the graviton, the particle that would carry the gravitational force, and sparticles, supersymmetric partners of the ordinary particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The 12 fundamental fermions are divided into 3 generations of 4 particles each.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Half of the fermions are leptons, three of which have an electric charge of −1 *e*, called the electron (e− ), the muon (μ− ), and the tau (τ− ); the other three leptons are neutrinos (ν e, ν μ, ν τ), which are the only elementary fermions with neither electric nor color charge.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The remaining six particles are quarks (discussed below).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The following table lists current measured masses and mass estimates for all the fermions, using the same scale of measure: millions of electron-volts relative to square of light speed (MeV/*c*2).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] For example, the most accurately known quark mass is of the top quark (t) at 172.7 GeV/*c*2, estimated using the on-shell scheme.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Estimates of the values of quark masses depend on the version of quantum chromodynamics used to describe quark interactions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Quarks are always confined in an envelope of gluons that confer vastly greater mass to the mesons and baryons where quarks occur, so values for quark masses cannot be measured directly.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Since their masses are so small compared to the effective mass of the surrounding gluons, slight differences in the calculation make large differences in the masses.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] There are also 12 fundamental fermionic antiparticles that correspond to these 12 particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] For example, the antielectron (positron) e+ is the electron's antiparticle and has an electric charge of +1 *e*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Isolated quarks and antiquarks have never been detected, a fact explained by confinement.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Every quark carries one of three color charges of the strong interaction; antiquarks similarly carry anticolor.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Color-charged particles interact via gluon exchange in the same way that charged particles interact via photon exchange.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Gluons are themselves color-charged, however, resulting in an amplification of the strong force as color-charged particles are separated.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Unlike the electromagnetic force, which diminishes as charged particles separate, color-charged particles feel increasing force.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Nonetheless, color-charged particles may combine to form color neutral composite particles called hadrons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] A quark may pair up with an antiquark: the quark has a color and the antiquark has the corresponding anticolor.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The color and anticolor cancel out, forming a color neutral meson.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Alternatively, three quarks can exist together, one quark being "red", another "blue", another "green".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] These three colored quarks together form a color-neutral baryon.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Symmetrically, three antiquarks with the colors "antired", "antiblue" and "antigreen" can form a color-neutral antibaryon.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Quarks also carry fractional electric charges, but, since they are confined within hadrons whose charges are all integral, fractional charges have never been isolated.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Note that quarks have electric charges of either ⁠++2/3⁠ *e* or ⁠−+1/3⁠ *e*, whereas antiquarks have corresponding electric charges of either ⁠−+2/3⁠ *e* or ⁠++1/3⁠ *e*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Evidence for the existence of quarks comes from deep inelastic scattering: firing electrons at nuclei to determine the distribution of charge within nucleons (which are baryons).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] If the charge is uniform, the electric field around the proton should be uniform and the electron should scatter elastically.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Low-energy electrons do scatter in this way, but, above a particular energy, the protons deflect some electrons through large angles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The recoiling electron has much less energy and a jet of particles is emitted.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] This inelastic scattering suggests that the charge in the proton is not uniform but split among smaller charged particles: quarks.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] In the Standard Model, vector (spin-1) bosons (gluons, photons, and the W and Z bosons) mediate forces, whereas the Higgs boson (spin-0) is responsible for the intrinsic mass of particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Bosons differ from fermions in the fact that multiple bosons can occupy the same quantum state (Pauli exclusion principle).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Also, bosons can be either elementary, like photons, or a combination, like mesons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The spin of bosons are integers instead of half integers.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Gluons mediate the strong interaction, which join quarks and thereby form hadrons, which are either baryons (three quarks) or mesons (one quark and one antiquark).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Protons and neutrons are baryons, joined by gluons to form the atomic nucleus.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Like quarks, gluons exhibit color and anticolor – unrelated to the concept of visual color and rather the particles' strong interactions – sometimes in combinations, altogether eight variations of gluons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] There are three weak gauge bosons: W+, W−, and Z0; these mediate the weak interaction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The W bosons are known for their mediation in nuclear decay: The W− converts a neutron into a proton then decays into an electron and electron-antineutrino pair.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The Z0 does not convert particle flavor or charges, but rather changes momentum; it is the only mechanism for elastically scattering neutrinos.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The weak gauge bosons were discovered due to momentum change in electrons from neutrino-Z exchange.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The massless photon mediates the electromagnetic interaction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] These four gauge bosons form the electroweak interaction among elementary particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Although the weak and electromagnetic forces appear quite different to us at everyday energies, the two forces are theorized to unify as a single electroweak force at high energies.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] This prediction was clearly confirmed by measurements of cross-sections for high-energy electron-proton scattering at the HERA collider at DESY.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The differences at low energies is a consequence of the high masses of the W and Z bosons, which in turn are a consequence of the Higgs mechanism.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Through the process of spontaneous symmetry breaking, the Higgs selects a special direction in electroweak space that causes three electroweak particles to become very heavy (the weak bosons) and one to remain with an undefined rest mass as it is always in motion (the photon).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] On 4 July 2012, after many years of experimentally searching for evidence of its existence, the Higgs boson was announced to have been observed at CERN's Large Hadron Collider.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Peter Higgs who first posited the existence of the Higgs boson was present at the announcement.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The Higgs boson is believed to have a mass of approximately 125 GeV/*c*2.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The statistical significance of this discovery was reported as 5 sigma, which implies a certainty of roughly 99.99994%.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] In particle physics, this is the level of significance required to officially label experimental observations as a discovery.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Research into the properties of the newly discovered particle continues.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Although experimental evidence overwhelmingly confirms the Standard Model’s predictions, some aspects of the theory remain poorly understood, such as the reason for the extremely large discrepancy between the weak force and gravity (an aspect of the hierarchy problem).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] A further issue is the fact that several of the parameters of the theory were introduced *ad hoc* rather than emerging naturally from an underlying physical explanation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Theories beyond the Standard Model attempt to resolve these perceived shortcomings.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The graviton is a hypothetical elementary spin-2 particle proposed to mediate gravitation.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] While it remains undiscovered due to the difficulty inherent in its detection, it is sometimes included in tables of elementary particles.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The conventional graviton is massless, although some models containing massive Kaluza–Klein gravitons exist.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] One extension of the Standard Model attempts to combine the electroweak interaction with the strong interaction into a single 'grand unified theory' (GUT).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Such a force would be spontaneously broken into the three forces by a Higgs-like mechanism.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] This breakdown is theorized to occur at high energies, making it difficult to observe unification in a laboratory.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The most dramatic prediction of grand unification is the existence of X and Y bosons, which cause proton decay.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The non-observation of proton decay at the Super-Kamiokande neutrino observatory rules out the simplest GUTs, however, including SU(5) and SO(10).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Supersymmetry extends the Standard Model by adding another class of symmetries to the Lagrangian.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] These symmetries exchange fermionic particles with bosonic ones.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Such a symmetry predicts the existence of supersymmetric particles, abbreviated as *sparticles*, which include the sleptons, squarks, neutralinos, and charginos.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Each particle in the Standard Model would have a superpartner whose spin differs by 1⁄2 from the ordinary particle.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Due to the breaking of supersymmetry, the sparticles are much heavier than their ordinary counterparts; they are so heavy that existing particle colliders would not be powerful enough to produce them.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Some physicists believe that sparticles will be detected by the Large Hadron Collider at CERN.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] String theory is a model of physics whereby all "particles" that make up matter are composed of strings (measuring at the Planck length) that exist in an 11-dimensional (according to M-theory, the leading version) or 12-dimensional (according to F-theory) universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] These strings vibrate at different frequencies that determine mass, electric charge, color charge, and spin.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] A "string" can be open (a line) or closed in a loop (a one-dimensional sphere, that is, a circle).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] As a string moves through space it sweeps out something called a *world sheet*.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] String theory proposes that our universe is merely a 4-brane, inside which exist the three space dimensions and the one time dimension that we observe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The remaining 7 theoretical dimensions either are very tiny and curled up (and too small to be macroscopically accessible) or simply do not/cannot exist in our universe (because they exist in a grander scheme called the "multiverse" outside our known universe).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Some predictions of the string theory include existence of extremely massive counterparts of ordinary particles due to vibrational excitations of the fundamental string and existence of a massless spin-2 particle behaving like the graviton.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Technicolor theories try to modify the Standard Model in a minimal way by introducing a new QCD-like interaction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] This means one adds a new theory of so-called Techniquarks, interacting via so called Technigluons.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The main idea is that the Higgs boson is not an elementary particle but a bound state of these objects.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] According to preon theory there are one or more orders of particles more fundamental than those (or most of those) found in the Standard Model.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] The most fundamental of these are normally called preons, which is derived from "pre-quarks".
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] In essence, preon theory tries to do for the Standard Model what the Standard Model did for the particle zoo that came before it.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Most models assume that almost everything in the Standard Model can be explained in terms of three to six more fundamental particles and the rules that govern their interactions.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Interest in preons has waned since the simplest models were experimentally ruled out in the 1980s.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Accelerons are the hypothetical subatomic particles that integrally link the newfound mass of the neutrino to the dark energy conjectured to be accelerating the expansion of the universe.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] In this theory, neutrinos are influenced by a new force resulting from their interactions with accelerons, leading to dark energy.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Dark energy results as the universe tries to pull neutrinos apart.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/elementary-particle] Accelerons are thought to interact with matter more infrequently than they do with neutrinos.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/minimum-total-potential-energy-principle] The **minimum total potential energy principle** is a fundamental concept used in physics and engineering.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/minimum-total-potential-energy-principle] It dictates that at low temperatures a structure or body shall deform or displace to a position that (locally) minimizes the total potential energy, with the lost potential energy being converted into kinetic energy (specifically heat).
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/minimum-total-potential-energy-principle] The principle of minimum total potential energy may be derived as a special case of the virtual work principle for elastic systems subject to conservative forces.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/minimum-total-potential-energy-principle] In the special case of elastic bodies, the right-hand-side of (**3**) can be taken to be the change, $\delta \mathbf {U}$ , of elastic strain energy **U** due to infinitesimal variations of real displacements.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/minimum-total-potential-energy-principle] In addition, when the external forces are conservative forces, the left-hand-side of (**3**) can be seen as the change in the potential energy function **V** of the forces.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/minimum-total-potential-energy-principle] The function **V** is defined as: $\mathbf {V} =-\int _{S_{t}}\mathbf {u} ^{T}\mathbf {T} dS-\int _{V}\mathbf {u} ^{T}\mathbf {f} dV$ where the minus sign implies a loss of potential energy as the force is displaced in its direction.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/minimum-total-potential-energy-principle] With these two subsidiary conditions, **Equation 3** becomes: $-\delta \ \mathbf {V} =\delta \ \mathbf {U}$ This leads to (**2**) as desired.
[src:minimum-total-potential-energy-principle/minimum-total-potential-energy-principle] The variational form of (**2**) is often used as the basis for developing the finite element method in structural mechanics.
